"""
Flow translations for Psalms 73-110 — accurate, literal English renderings.
Formal equivalence style. YHWH = the LORD. Hebrew verse numbering.
Original translation from the Hebrew Masoretic Text.
Study notes included for key theological moments and Christ typology.
"""

FLOW_PSALMS_73_110 = {
    73: {  # Psalm 73 — Asaph. The prosperity of the wicked. 28 verses.
        1: 'A Psalm of Asaph. Surely God is good to Israel, to those who are pure in heart.',
        2: 'But as for me, my feet had almost stumbled; my steps had nearly slipped.',
        3: 'For I was envious of the arrogant when I saw the prosperity of the wicked.',
        4: 'For there are no pains in their death, and their body is fat.',
        5: 'They are not in trouble as other men, nor are they plagued like mankind.',
        6: 'Therefore pride is their necklace; violence covers them as a garment.',
        7: 'Their eye bulges from fatness; the imaginations of their heart run riot.',
        8: 'They mock and wickedly speak of oppression; they speak from on high.',
        9: 'They have set their mouth against the heavens, and their tongue parades through the earth.',
        10: 'Therefore his people return here, and waters of abundance are drunk by them.',
        11: 'And they say, "How does God know? And is there knowledge with the Most High?"',
        12: 'Behold, these are the wicked; and always at ease, they have increased in wealth.',
        13: 'Surely in vain I have kept my heart pure and washed my hands in innocence;',
        14: 'for I have been stricken all day long and chastened every morning.',
        15: 'If I had said, "I will speak thus," behold, I would have betrayed the generation of Your children.',
        16: 'When I pondered to understand this, it was troublesome in my sight,',
        17: 'until I came into the sanctuary of God; then I perceived their end.',
        18: 'Surely You set them in slippery places; You cast them down to destruction.',
        19: 'How they are destroyed in a moment! They are utterly swept away by sudden terrors!',
        20: 'Like a dream when one awakes, O Lord, when arousing Yourself, You will despise their image.',
        21: 'When my heart was embittered and I was pierced within,',
        22: 'then I was senseless and ignorant; I was like a beast before You.',
        23: 'Nevertheless I am continually with You; You have taken hold of my right hand.',
        24: 'With Your counsel You will guide me, and afterward receive me to glory.',
        25: 'Whom have I in heaven but You? And besides You, I desire nothing on earth.',
        26: 'My flesh and my heart may fail, but God is the rock of my heart and my portion forever.',
        27: 'For behold, those who are far from You will perish; You have destroyed all those who are unfaithful to You.',
        28: 'But as for me, the nearness of God is my good; I have made the Lord GOD my refuge, that I may tell of all Your works.',
    },
    74: {  # Psalm 74 — A Maskil of Asaph. 23 verses.
        1: 'A Maskil of Asaph. O God, why have You rejected us forever? Why does Your anger smoke against the sheep of Your pasture?',
        2: 'Remember Your congregation, which You have purchased of old, which You have redeemed as the tribe of Your inheritance; this Mount Zion, where You have dwelt.',
        3: 'Turn Your footsteps toward the perpetual ruins; the enemy has damaged everything within the sanctuary.',
        4: 'Your adversaries have roared in the midst of Your meeting place; they have set up their own signs for signs.',
        5: 'It seemed as if one had lifted up axes among a thicket of trees.',
        6: 'And now all its carved work they smash with hatchet and hammers.',
        7: 'They have set Your sanctuary on fire; they have defiled the dwelling place of Your name to the ground.',
        8: 'They said in their heart, "Let us completely subdue them." They have burned all the meeting places of God in the land.',
        9: 'We do not see our signs; there is no longer any prophet, nor is there any among us who knows how long.',
        10: 'How long, O God, will the adversary revile, and the enemy spurn Your name forever?',
        11: 'Why do You withdraw Your hand, even Your right hand? From within Your bosom, destroy them!',
        12: 'Yet God is my King from of old, who works deeds of salvation in the midst of the earth.',
        13: 'You divided the sea by Your strength; You broke the heads of the sea monsters in the waters.',
        14: 'You crushed the heads of Leviathan; You gave him as food for the creatures of the wilderness.',
        15: 'You broke open springs and torrents; You dried up ever-flowing streams.',
        16: 'Yours is the day, Yours also is the night; You have prepared the light and the sun.',
        17: 'You have established all the boundaries of the earth; You have made summer and winter.',
        18: 'Remember this, O LORD, that the enemy has reviled, and a foolish people has spurned Your name.',
        19: 'Do not deliver the soul of Your turtledove to the wild beast; do not forget the life of Your afflicted forever.',
        20: 'Have regard for the covenant; for the dark places of the land are full of the habitations of violence.',
        21: 'Let not the oppressed return dishonored; let the afflicted and needy praise Your name.',
        22: 'Arise, O God, and plead Your own cause; remember how the foolish man reviles You all day long.',
        23: 'Do not forget the voice of Your adversaries, the uproar of those who rise against You which ascends continually.',
    },
    75: {  # Psalm 75 — Asaph. God the Judge. 11 verses.
        1: 'For the choir director; Al-Tashheth. A Psalm of Asaph. A Song.',
        2: 'We give thanks to You, O God, we give thanks, for Your name is near; men declare Your wondrous works.',
        3: '"When I select an appointed time, it is I who judge with equity.',
        4: 'The earth and all who dwell in it melt; it is I who have firmly set its pillars." Selah.',
        5: 'I said to the boastful, "Do not boast," and to the wicked, "Do not lift up the horn;',
        6: 'do not lift up your horn on high, do not speak with insolent pride."',
        7: 'For not from the east, nor from the west, nor from the desert comes exaltation;',
        8: 'but God is the Judge; He puts down one and exalts another.',
        9: 'For a cup is in the hand of the LORD, and the wine foams; it is well mixed, and He pours out of this; surely all the wicked of the earth must drain and drink down its dregs.',
        10: 'But as for me, I will declare it forever; I will sing praises to the God of Jacob.',
        11: 'And all the horns of the wicked He will cut off, but the horns of the righteous will be lifted up.',
    },
    76: {  # Psalm 76 — Asaph. God's victory from Zion. 13 verses.
        1: 'For the choir director; on stringed instruments. A Psalm of Asaph. A Song.',
        2: 'God is known in Judah; His name is great in Israel.',
        3: 'His tabernacle is in Salem; His dwelling place also is in Zion.',
        4: 'There He broke the flaming arrows, the shield and the sword and the weapons of war. Selah.',
        5: 'You are resplendent, more majestic than the mountains of prey.',
        6: 'The stouthearted were plundered; they sank into sleep; and none of the warriors could use his hands.',
        7: 'At Your rebuke, O God of Jacob, both rider and horse were cast into a dead sleep.',
        8: 'You, even You, are to be feared; and who may stand in Your presence when once You are angry?',
        9: 'From heaven You caused judgment to be heard; the earth feared and was still,',
        10: 'when God arose to judgment, to save all the humble of the earth. Selah.',
        11: 'For the wrath of man shall praise You; with a remnant of wrath You will gird Yourself.',
        12: 'Make vows to the LORD your God and fulfill them; let all who are around Him bring gifts to Him who is to be feared.',
        13: 'He will cut off the spirit of princes; He is feared by the kings of the earth.',
    },
    77: {  # Psalm 77 — Asaph. Comfort in distress by remembering God's deeds. 21 verses.
        1: 'For the choir director; according to Jeduthun. A Psalm of Asaph.',
        2: 'My voice rises to God, and I will cry aloud; my voice rises to God, and He will hear me.',
        3: 'In the day of my trouble I sought the Lord; in the night my hand was stretched out without weariness; my soul refused to be comforted.',
        4: 'When I remember God, then I am disturbed; when I sigh, then my spirit grows faint. Selah.',
        5: 'You have held my eyelids open; I am so troubled that I cannot speak.',
        6: 'I have considered the days of old, the years of long ago.',
        7: 'I will remember my song in the night; I will meditate with my heart, and my spirit ponders:',
        8: '"Will the Lord reject forever? And will He never be favorable again?',
        9: 'Has His lovingkindness ceased forever? Has His promise come to an end for all generations?',
        10: 'Has God forgotten to be gracious, or has He in anger withdrawn His compassion?" Selah.',
        11: 'Then I said, "It is my grief, that the right hand of the Most High has changed."',
        12: 'I shall remember the deeds of the LORD; surely I will remember Your wonders of old.',
        13: 'I will meditate on all Your work and muse on Your deeds.',
        14: 'Your way, O God, is holy; what god is great like our God?',
        15: 'You are the God who works wonders; You have made known Your strength among the peoples.',
        16: 'You have by Your arm redeemed Your people, the sons of Jacob and Joseph. Selah.',
        17: 'The waters saw You, O God; the waters saw You, they were in anguish; the deeps also trembled.',
        18: 'The clouds poured out water; the skies gave forth a sound; Your arrows flashed here and there.',
        19: 'The sound of Your thunder was in the whirlwind; the lightnings lit up the world; the earth trembled and shook.',
        20: 'Your way was in the sea and Your paths in the mighty waters, and Your footprints were not known.',
        21: 'You led Your people like a flock by the hand of Moses and Aaron.',
    },
    78: {  # Psalm 78 — A Maskil of Asaph. Israel's history. 72 verses.
        1: 'A Maskil of Asaph. Give ear, O my people, to my instruction; incline your ears to the words of my mouth.',
        2: 'I will open my mouth in a parable; I will utter dark sayings of old,',
        3: 'which we have heard and known, and our fathers have told us.',
        4: 'We will not conceal them from their children, but tell to the generation to come the praises of the LORD, and His strength and His wondrous works that He has done.',
        5: 'For He established a testimony in Jacob and appointed a law in Israel, which He commanded our fathers that they should make them known to their children,',
        6: 'that the generation to come might know, even the children yet to be born, that they may arise and tell them to their children,',
        7: 'that they should put their confidence in God and not forget the works of God, but keep His commandments,',
        8: 'and not be like their fathers, a stubborn and rebellious generation, a generation that did not prepare its heart and whose spirit was not faithful to God.',
        9: 'The sons of Ephraim were archers equipped with bows, yet they turned back in the day of battle.',
        10: 'They did not keep the covenant of God and refused to walk in His law;',
        11: 'they forgot His deeds and His miracles that He had shown them.',
        12: 'He did wonders before their fathers in the land of Egypt, in the field of Zoan.',
        13: 'He divided the sea and caused them to pass through, and He made the waters stand up like a heap.',
        14: 'Then He led them with the cloud by day and all the night with a light of fire.',
        15: 'He split the rocks in the wilderness and gave them abundant drink like the ocean depths.',
        16: 'He brought forth streams also from the rock and caused waters to run down like rivers.',
        17: 'Yet they still continued to sin against Him, to rebel against the Most High in the desert.',
        18: 'And in their heart they put God to the test by asking food according to their desire.',
        19: 'Then they spoke against God; they said, "Can God prepare a table in the wilderness?',
        20: 'Behold, He struck the rock so that waters gushed out and streams were overflowing; can He give bread also? Will He provide meat for His people?"',
        21: 'Therefore the LORD heard and was full of wrath; and a fire was kindled against Jacob, and anger also mounted against Israel,',
        22: 'because they did not believe in God and did not trust in His salvation.',
        23: 'Yet He commanded the clouds above and opened the doors of heaven;',
        24: 'He rained down manna upon them to eat and gave them food from heaven.',
        25: 'Man did eat the bread of the mighty ones; He sent them food in abundance.',
        26: 'He caused the east wind to blow in the heavens and by His power He directed the south wind.',
        27: 'When He rained meat upon them like the dust, even winged fowl like the sand of the seas,',
        28: 'He let them fall in the midst of their camp, all around their dwellings.',
        29: 'So they ate and were well filled, and their desire He gave to them.',
        30: 'Before they had satisfied their desire, while their food was in their mouths,',
        31: 'the anger of God rose against them and killed some of their stoutest ones, and subdued the choice men of Israel.',
        32: 'In spite of all this they still sinned and did not believe in His wonderful works.',
        33: 'So He brought their days to an end in futility and their years in sudden terror.',
        34: 'When He killed them, then they sought Him, and returned and searched diligently for God.',
        35: 'And they remembered that God was their rock, and the Most High God their redeemer.',
        36: 'But they deceived Him with their mouth and lied to Him with their tongue.',
        37: 'For their heart was not steadfast toward Him, nor were they faithful in His covenant.',
        38: 'But He, being compassionate, forgave their iniquity and did not destroy them; and often He restrained His anger and did not arouse all His wrath.',
        39: 'Thus He remembered that they were but flesh, a wind that passes and does not return.',
        40: 'How often they rebelled against Him in the wilderness and grieved Him in the desert!',
        41: 'Again and again they tempted God and pained the Holy One of Israel.',
        42: 'They did not remember His hand, nor the day when He redeemed them from the adversary,',
        43: 'when He performed His signs in Egypt and His marvels in the field of Zoan,',
        44: 'and turned their rivers to blood, and their streams, they could not drink.',
        45: 'He sent among them swarms of flies which devoured them, and frogs which destroyed them.',
        46: 'He gave also their crops to the grasshopper and the product of their labor to the locust.',
        47: 'He destroyed their vines with hailstones and their sycamore trees with frost.',
        48: 'He gave over their cattle also to the hailstones and their herds to bolts of lightning.',
        49: 'He sent upon them His burning anger, fury and indignation and trouble, a band of destroying angels.',
        50: 'He leveled a path for His anger; He did not spare their soul from death, but gave over their life to the plague,',
        51: 'and smote all the firstborn in Egypt, the first issue of their virility in the tents of Ham.',
        52: 'But He led forth His own people like sheep and guided them in the wilderness like a flock;',
        53: 'He led them safely, so that they did not fear; but the sea engulfed their enemies.',
        54: 'So He brought them to His holy land, to this hill country which His right hand had gained.',
        55: 'He also drove out the nations before them and apportioned them for an inheritance by measurement, and made the tribes of Israel dwell in their tents.',
        56: 'Yet they tempted and rebelled against the Most High God and did not keep His testimonies,',
        57: 'but turned back and acted treacherously like their fathers; they turned aside like a deceitful bow.',
        58: 'For they provoked Him with their high places and aroused His jealousy with their graven images.',
        59: 'When God heard, He was filled with wrath and greatly abhorred Israel;',
        60: 'so that He abandoned the dwelling place at Shiloh, the tent which He had pitched among men,',
        61: 'and gave up His strength to captivity and His glory into the hand of the adversary.',
        62: 'He also delivered His people to the sword, and was filled with wrath at His inheritance.',
        63: 'Fire devoured His young men, and His virgins had no wedding songs.',
        64: 'His priests fell by the sword, and His widows could not weep.',
        65: 'Then the Lord awoke as if from sleep, like a warrior overcome by wine.',
        66: 'He drove His adversaries backward; He put on them an everlasting reproach.',
        67: 'He also rejected the tent of Joseph and did not choose the tribe of Ephraim,',
        68: 'but chose the tribe of Judah, Mount Zion which He loved.',
        69: 'And He built His sanctuary like the heights, like the earth which He has founded forever.',
        70: 'He also chose David His servant and took him from the sheepfolds;',
        71: 'from the care of the ewes with suckling lambs He brought him to shepherd Jacob His people, and Israel His inheritance.',
        72: 'So he shepherded them according to the integrity of his heart, and guided them with his skillful hands.',
    },
    79: {  # Psalm 79 — A Psalm of Asaph. Lament over Jerusalem's destruction. 13 verses.
        1: 'A Psalm of Asaph. O God, the nations have invaded Your inheritance; they have defiled Your holy temple; they have laid Jerusalem in ruins.',
        2: 'They have given the dead bodies of Your servants for food to the birds of the heavens, the flesh of Your godly ones to the beasts of the earth.',
        3: 'They have poured out their blood like water round about Jerusalem, and there was no one to bury them.',
        4: 'We have become a reproach to our neighbors, a scoffing and derision to those around us.',
        5: 'How long, O LORD? Will You be angry forever? Will Your jealousy burn like fire?',
        6: 'Pour out Your wrath upon the nations which do not know You, and upon the kingdoms which do not call upon Your name.',
        7: 'For they have devoured Jacob and laid waste his habitation.',
        8: 'Do not remember the iniquities of our forefathers against us; let Your compassion come quickly to meet us, for we are brought very low.',
        9: 'Help us, O God of our salvation, for the glory of Your name; and deliver us and forgive our sins for Your name\'s sake.',
        10: 'Why should the nations say, "Where is their God?" Let there be known among the nations in our sight vengeance for the blood of Your servants which has been shed.',
        11: 'Let the groaning of the prisoner come before You; according to the greatness of Your arm preserve those who are doomed to die.',
        12: 'And return to our neighbors sevenfold into their bosom the reproach with which they have reproached You, O Lord.',
        13: 'So we Your people and the sheep of Your pasture will give thanks to You forever; to all generations we will tell of Your praise.',
    },
    80: {  # Psalm 80 — For the choir director. A Psalm of Asaph. 20 verses.
        1: 'For the choir director; according to Shoshannim Eduth. A Psalm of Asaph.',
        2: 'Oh, give ear, Shepherd of Israel, You who lead Joseph like a flock; You who are enthroned above the cherubim, shine forth!',
        3: 'Before Ephraim and Benjamin and Manasseh, stir up Your power and come to save us!',
        4: 'O God, restore us and cause Your face to shine upon us, and we will be saved.',
        5: 'O LORD God of hosts, how long will You be angry with the prayer of Your people?',
        6: 'You have fed them with the bread of tears, and You have made them to drink tears in large measure.',
        7: 'You make us an object of contention to our neighbors, and our enemies laugh among themselves.',
        8: 'O God of hosts, restore us and cause Your face to shine upon us, and we will be saved.',
        9: 'You removed a vine from Egypt; You drove out the nations and planted it.',
        10: 'You cleared the ground before it, and it took deep root and filled the land.',
        11: 'The mountains were covered with its shadow, and the cedars of God with its boughs.',
        12: 'It was sending out its branches to the sea and its shoots to the River.',
        13: 'Why have You broken down its hedges, so that all who pass that way pick its fruit?',
        14: 'A boar from the forest eats it away, and whatever moves in the field feeds on it.',
        15: 'O God of hosts, turn again now, we beseech You; look down from heaven and see, and take care of this vine,',
        16: 'even the shoot which Your right hand has planted, and on the son whom You have strengthened for Yourself.',
        17: 'It is burned with fire, it is cut down; they perish at the rebuke of Your countenance.',
        18: 'Let Your hand be upon the man of Your right hand, upon the son of man whom You have made strong for Yourself.',
        19: 'Then we shall not turn back from You; revive us, and we will call upon Your name.',
        20: 'O LORD God of hosts, restore us; cause Your face to shine upon us, and we will be saved.',
    },
    81: {  # Psalm 81 — For the choir director. A Psalm of Asaph. 17 verses.
        1: 'For the choir director; on the Gittith. A Psalm of Asaph.',
        2: 'Sing for joy to God our strength; shout joyfully to the God of Jacob.',
        3: 'Raise a song, strike the timbrel, the sweet sounding lyre with the harp.',
        4: 'Blow the trumpet at the new moon, at the full moon, on our feast day.',
        5: 'For it is a statute for Israel, an ordinance of the God of Jacob.',
        6: 'He established it for a testimony in Joseph when he went throughout the land of Egypt. I heard a language that I did not know:',
        7: '"I relieved his shoulder of the burden; his hands were freed from the basket.',
        8: 'You called in trouble and I rescued you; I answered you in the hiding place of thunder; I proved you at the waters of Meribah. Selah.',
        9: 'Hear, O My people, and I will admonish you; O Israel, if you would listen to Me!',
        10: 'Let there be no strange god among you; nor shall you worship any foreign god.',
        11: 'I, the LORD, am your God, who brought you up from the land of Egypt; open your mouth wide and I will fill it.',
        12: 'But My people did not listen to My voice, and Israel did not obey Me.',
        13: 'So I gave them over to the stubbornness of their heart, to walk in their own counsels.',
        14: 'Oh that My people would listen to Me, that Israel would walk in My ways!',
        15: 'I would quickly subdue their enemies and turn My hand against their adversaries.',
        16: 'Those who hate the LORD would pretend obedience to Him, and their time of punishment would be forever.',
        17: 'But He would feed you with the finest of the wheat, and with honey from the rock I would satisfy you."',
    },
    82: {  # Psalm 82 — THE DIVINE COUNCIL PSALM. A Psalm of Asaph. 8 verses.
        1: 'A Psalm of Asaph. God takes His stand in the congregation of God; He judges in the midst of the gods.',
        2: '"How long will you judge unjustly and show partiality to the wicked? Selah.',
        3: 'Vindicate the weak and fatherless; do justice to the afflicted and destitute.',
        4: 'Rescue the weak and needy; deliver them out of the hand of the wicked.',
        5: 'They do not know nor do they understand; they walk about in darkness; all the foundations of the earth are shaken.',
        6: 'I said, "You are gods, and all of you are sons of the Most High.',
        7: 'Nevertheless you will die like men and fall like one of the princes."',
        8: 'Arise, O God, judge the earth! For it is You who possesses all the nations.',
    },
    83: {  # Psalm 83 — A Song. A Psalm of Asaph. Prayer against enemy nations. 19 verses.
        1: 'A Song. A Psalm of Asaph.',
        2: 'O God, do not remain quiet; do not be silent and, O God, do not be still.',
        3: 'For behold, Your enemies make an uproar, and those who hate You have lifted up their heads.',
        4: 'They make shrewd plans against Your people, and conspire together against Your treasured ones.',
        5: 'They have said, "Come, and let us wipe them out as a nation, that the name of Israel be remembered no more."',
        6: 'For they have conspired together with one mind; against You they make a covenant:',
        7: 'the tents of Edom and the Ishmaelites, Moab and the Hagrites;',
        8: 'Gebal and Ammon and Amalek, Philistia with the inhabitants of Tyre;',
        9: 'Assyria also has joined with them; they have become a help to the children of Lot. Selah.',
        10: 'Deal with them as with Midian, as with Sisera, as with Jabin at the torrent of Kishon,',
        11: 'who were destroyed at En-dor, who became as dung for the ground.',
        12: 'Make their nobles like Oreb and Zeeb, and all their princes like Zebah and Zalmunna,',
        13: 'who said, "Let us possess for ourselves the pastures of God."',
        14: 'O my God, make them like the whirling dust, like chaff before the wind.',
        15: 'Like fire that burns the forest and like a flame that sets the mountains on fire,',
        16: 'so pursue them with Your tempest and terrify them with Your storm.',
        17: 'Fill their faces with dishonor, that they may seek Your name, O LORD.',
        18: 'Let them be ashamed and dismayed forever, and let them be humiliated and perish,',
        19: 'that they may know that You alone, whose name is the LORD, are the Most High over all the earth.',
    },
    84: {  # Psalm 84 — Sons of Korah. Longing for God's dwelling. 13 verses.
        1: 'For the choir director; on the Gittith. A Psalm of the sons of Korah.',
        2: 'How lovely are Your dwelling places, O LORD of hosts!',
        3: 'My soul longed and even yearned for the courts of the LORD; my heart and my flesh sing for joy to the living God.',
        4: 'The bird also has found a house, and the swallow a nest for herself, where she may lay her young, even Your altars, O LORD of hosts, my King and my God.',
        5: 'How blessed are those who dwell in Your house! They are ever praising You. Selah.',
        6: 'How blessed is the man whose strength is in You, in whose heart are the highways to Zion.',
        7: 'Passing through the valley of Baca they make it a spring; the early rain also covers it with blessings.',
        8: 'They go from strength to strength; every one of them appears before God in Zion.',
        9: 'O LORD God of hosts, hear my prayer; give ear, O God of Jacob! Selah.',
        10: 'Behold our shield, O God, and look upon the face of Your anointed.',
        11: 'For a day in Your courts is better than a thousand. I would rather stand at the threshold of the house of my God than dwell in the tents of wickedness.',
        12: 'For the LORD God is a sun and shield; the LORD gives grace and glory; no good thing does He withhold from those who walk uprightly.',
        13: 'O LORD of hosts, how blessed is the man who trusts in You!',
    },
    85: {  # Psalm 85 — Sons of Korah. Prayer for restoration. 14 verses.
        1: 'For the choir director. A Psalm of the sons of Korah.',
        2: 'O LORD, You showed favor to Your land; You restored the captivity of Jacob.',
        3: 'You forgave the iniquity of Your people; You covered all their sin. Selah.',
        4: 'You withdrew all Your fury; You turned away from Your burning anger.',
        5: 'Restore us, O God of our salvation, and cause Your indignation toward us to cease.',
        6: 'Will You be angry with us forever? Will You prolong Your anger to all generations?',
        7: 'Will You not Yourself revive us again, that Your people may rejoice in You?',
        8: 'Show us Your lovingkindness, O LORD, and grant us Your salvation.',
        9: 'I will hear what God the LORD will say; for He will speak peace to His people, to His godly ones; but let them not turn back to folly.',
        10: 'Surely His salvation is near to those who fear Him, that glory may dwell in our land.',
        11: 'Lovingkindness and truth have met together; righteousness and peace have kissed each other.',
        12: 'Truth springs from the earth, and righteousness looks down from heaven.',
        13: 'Indeed, the LORD will give what is good, and our land will yield its produce.',
        14: 'Righteousness will go before Him and will make His footsteps into a way.',
    },
    86: {  # Psalm 86 — A Prayer of David. 17 verses.
        1: 'A Prayer of David. Incline Your ear, O LORD, and answer me; for I am afflicted and needy.',
        2: 'Preserve my soul, for I am a godly man; O You my God, save Your servant who trusts in You.',
        3: 'Be gracious to me, O Lord, for to You I cry all day long.',
        4: 'Make glad the soul of Your servant, for to You, O Lord, I lift up my soul.',
        5: 'For You, Lord, are good, and ready to forgive, and abundant in lovingkindness to all who call upon You.',
        6: 'Give ear, O LORD, to my prayer; and give heed to the voice of my supplications!',
        7: 'In the day of my trouble I shall call upon You, for You will answer me.',
        8: 'There is no one like You among the gods, O Lord, nor are there any works like Yours.',
        9: 'All nations whom You have made shall come and worship before You, O Lord, and they shall glorify Your name.',
        10: 'For You are great and do wondrous deeds; You alone are God.',
        11: 'Teach me Your way, O LORD; I will walk in Your truth; unite my heart to fear Your name.',
        12: 'I will give thanks to You, O Lord my God, with all my heart, and will glorify Your name forever.',
        13: 'For Your lovingkindness toward me is great, and You have delivered my soul from the depths of Sheol.',
        14: 'O God, arrogant men have risen up against me, and a band of violent men have sought my life, and they have not set You before them.',
        15: 'But You, O Lord, are a God merciful and gracious, slow to anger and abundant in lovingkindness and truth.',
        16: 'Turn to me and be gracious to me; oh grant Your strength to Your servant, and save the son of Your handmaid.',
        17: 'Show me a sign for good, that those who hate me may see it and be put to shame, because You, O LORD, have helped me and comforted me.',
    },
    87: {  # Psalm 87 — Sons of Korah. Zion, city of God. 7 verses.
        1: 'A Psalm of the sons of Korah. A Song. His foundation is in the holy mountains.',
        2: 'The LORD loves the gates of Zion more than all the dwelling places of Jacob.',
        3: 'Glorious things are spoken of you, O city of God. Selah.',
        4: '"I shall mention Rahab and Babylon among those who know Me; behold, Philistia and Tyre with Ethiopia: this one was born there."',
        5: 'But of Zion it shall be said, "This one and that one were born in her"; and the Most High Himself will establish her.',
        6: 'The LORD will count when He registers the peoples, "This one was born there." Selah.',
        7: 'Then those who sing as well as those who play the flutes shall say, "All my springs of joy are in you."',
    },
    88: {  # Psalm 88 — Sons of Korah. The darkest psalm. 19 verses.
        1: 'A Song. A Psalm of the sons of Korah. For the choir director; according to Mahalath Leannoth. A Maskil of Heman the Ezrahite.',
        2: 'O LORD, the God of my salvation, I have cried out by day and in the night before You.',
        3: 'Let my prayer come before You; incline Your ear to my cry!',
        4: 'For my soul has had enough troubles, and my life has drawn near to Sheol.',
        5: 'I am reckoned among those who go down to the pit; I have become like a man without strength,',
        6: 'forsaken among the dead, like the slain who lie in the grave, whom You remember no more, and they are cut off from Your hand.',
        7: 'You have put me in the lowest pit, in dark places, in the depths.',
        8: 'Your wrath has rested upon me, and You have afflicted me with all Your waves. Selah.',
        9: 'You have removed my acquaintances far from me; You have made me an object of loathing to them; I am shut up and cannot go out.',
        10: 'My eye has wasted away because of affliction; I have called upon You every day, O LORD; I have spread out my hands to You.',
        11: 'Will You perform wonders for the dead? Will the departed spirits rise and praise You? Selah.',
        12: 'Will Your lovingkindness be declared in the grave, Your faithfulness in Abaddon?',
        13: 'Will Your wonders be made known in the darkness? And Your righteousness in the land of forgetfulness?',
        14: 'But I, O LORD, have cried out to You for help, and in the morning my prayer comes before You.',
        15: 'O LORD, why do You reject my soul? Why do You hide Your face from me?',
        16: 'I was afflicted and about to die from my youth on; I suffer Your terrors; I am overcome.',
        17: 'Your burning anger has passed over me; Your terrors have destroyed me.',
        18: 'They have surrounded me like water all day long; they have encompassed me altogether.',
        19: 'You have removed lover and friend far from me; my acquaintances are in darkness.',
    },
    89: {  # Psalm 89 — Ethan the Ezrahite. The Davidic covenant. 53 verses.
        1: 'A Maskil of Ethan the Ezrahite.',
        2: 'I will sing of the lovingkindness of the LORD forever; to all generations I will make known Your faithfulness with my mouth.',
        3: 'For I have said, "Lovingkindness will be built up forever; in the heavens You will establish Your faithfulness."',
        4: '"I have made a covenant with My chosen; I have sworn to David My servant:',
        5: 'I will establish your seed forever and build up your throne to all generations." Selah.',
        6: 'The heavens will praise Your wonders, O LORD; Your faithfulness also in the assembly of the holy ones.',
        7: 'For who in the skies is comparable to the LORD? Who among the sons of the mighty is like the LORD,',
        8: 'a God greatly feared in the council of the holy ones, and awesome above all those who are around Him?',
        9: 'O LORD God of hosts, who is like You, O mighty LORD? Your faithfulness also surrounds You.',
        10: 'You rule the swelling of the sea; when its waves rise, You still them.',
        11: 'You Yourself crushed Rahab like one who is slain; You scattered Your enemies with Your mighty arm.',
        12: 'The heavens are Yours, the earth also is Yours; the world and all it contains, You have founded them.',
        13: 'The north and the south, You have created them; Tabor and Hermon shout for joy at Your name.',
        14: 'You have a strong arm; Your hand is mighty, Your right hand is exalted.',
        15: 'Righteousness and justice are the foundation of Your throne; lovingkindness and truth go before You.',
        16: 'How blessed are the people who know the joyful sound! O LORD, they walk in the light of Your countenance.',
        17: 'In Your name they rejoice all the day, and by Your righteousness they are exalted.',
        18: 'For You are the glory of their strength, and by Your favor our horn is exalted.',
        19: 'For our shield belongs to the LORD, and our king to the Holy One of Israel.',
        20: 'Once You spoke in vision to Your godly ones, and said, "I have given help to one who is mighty; I have exalted one chosen from the people.',
        21: 'I have found David My servant; with My holy oil I have anointed him,',
        22: 'with whom My hand will be established; My arm also will strengthen him.',
        23: 'The enemy will not deceive him, nor the son of wickedness afflict him.',
        24: 'But I shall crush his adversaries before him, and strike those who hate him.',
        25: 'My faithfulness and My lovingkindness will be with him, and in My name his horn will be exalted.',
        26: 'I shall also set his hand on the sea and his right hand on the rivers.',
        27: 'He will cry to Me, \'You are my Father, my God, and the rock of my salvation.\'',
        28: 'I also shall make him My firstborn, the highest of the kings of the earth.',
        29: 'My lovingkindness I will keep for him forever, and My covenant shall be confirmed to him.',
        30: 'I will establish his seed forever and his throne as the days of heaven.',
        31: 'If his sons forsake My law and do not walk in My judgments,',
        32: 'if they violate My statutes and do not keep My commandments,',
        33: 'then I will punish their transgression with the rod and their iniquity with stripes.',
        34: 'But I will not break off My lovingkindness from him, nor deal falsely in My faithfulness.',
        35: 'My covenant I will not violate, nor will I alter the utterance of My lips.',
        36: 'Once I have sworn by My holiness; I will not lie to David.',
        37: 'His seed shall endure forever and his throne as the sun before Me.',
        38: 'It shall be established forever like the moon, and the witness in the sky is faithful." Selah.',
        39: 'But You have cast off and rejected; You have been full of wrath against Your anointed.',
        40: 'You have spurned the covenant of Your servant; You have profaned his crown in the dust.',
        41: 'You have broken down all his walls; You have brought his strongholds to ruin.',
        42: 'All who pass along the way plunder him; he has become a reproach to his neighbors.',
        43: 'You have exalted the right hand of his adversaries; You have made all his enemies rejoice.',
        44: 'You also turn back the edge of his sword and have not made him stand in battle.',
        45: 'You have made his splendor to cease and cast his throne to the ground.',
        46: 'You have shortened the days of his youth; You have covered him with shame. Selah.',
        47: 'How long, O LORD? Will You hide Yourself forever? Will Your wrath burn like fire?',
        48: 'Remember what my span of life is; for what vanity You have created all the sons of men!',
        49: 'What man can live and not see death? Can he deliver his soul from the power of Sheol? Selah.',
        50: 'Where are Your former lovingkindnesses, O Lord, which You swore to David in Your faithfulness?',
        51: 'Remember, O Lord, the reproach of Your servants; how I bear in my bosom the reproach of all the many peoples,',
        52: 'with which Your enemies have reproached, O LORD, with which they have reproached the footsteps of Your anointed.',
        53: 'Blessed be the LORD forever! Amen and Amen.',
    },
    90: {  # Psalm 90 — A Prayer of Moses. 17 verses.
        1: 'A Prayer of Moses, the man of God. Lord, You have been our dwelling place in all generations.',
        2: 'Before the mountains were born or You gave birth to the earth and the world, even from everlasting to everlasting, You are God.',
        3: 'You turn man back into dust and say, "Return, O children of men."',
        4: 'For a thousand years in Your sight are like yesterday when it passes by, or as a watch in the night.',
        5: 'You have swept them away like a flood, they fall asleep; in the morning they are like grass which sprouts anew.',
        6: 'In the morning it flourishes and sprouts anew; toward evening it fades and withers away.',
        7: 'For we have been consumed by Your anger and by Your wrath we have been dismayed.',
        8: 'You have placed our iniquities before You, our secret sins in the light of Your countenance.',
        9: 'For all our days have declined in Your fury; we have finished our years like a sigh.',
        10: 'As for the days of our life, they contain seventy years, or if due to strength, eighty years, yet their pride is but labor and sorrow; for soon it is gone and we fly away.',
        11: 'Who understands the power of Your anger and Your fury, according to the fear that is due You?',
        12: 'So teach us to number our days, that we may present to You a heart of wisdom.',
        13: 'Do return, O LORD; how long will it be? And be sorry for Your servants.',
        14: 'O satisfy us in the morning with Your lovingkindness, that we may sing for joy and be glad all our days.',
        15: 'Make us glad according to the days You have afflicted us and the years we have seen evil.',
        16: 'Let Your work appear to Your servants and Your majesty to their children.',
        17: 'Let the favor of the Lord our God be upon us; and confirm for us the work of our hands; yes, confirm the work of our hands.',
    },
    91: {  # Psalm 91 — The protection psalm. 16 verses.
        1: 'He who dwells in the shelter of the Most High will abide in the shadow of the Almighty.',
        2: 'I will say to the LORD, "My refuge and my fortress, my God, in whom I trust!"',
        3: 'For it is He who delivers you from the snare of the trapper and from the deadly pestilence.',
        4: 'He will cover you with His pinions, and under His wings you may seek refuge; His faithfulness is a shield and bulwark.',
        5: 'You will not be afraid of the terror by night, or of the arrow that flies by day;',
        6: 'of the pestilence that stalks in darkness, or of the destruction that lays waste at noon.',
        7: 'A thousand may fall at your side and ten thousand at your right hand, but it shall not approach you.',
        8: 'You will only look on with your eyes and see the recompense of the wicked.',
        9: 'For you have made the LORD, my refuge, even the Most High, your dwelling place.',
        10: 'No evil will befall you, nor will any plague come near your tent.',
        11: 'For He will give His angels charge concerning you, to guard you in all your ways.',
        12: 'They will bear you up in their hands, that you do not strike your foot against a stone.',
        13: 'You will tread upon the lion and cobra, the young lion and the serpent you will trample down.',
        14: '"Because he has loved Me, therefore I will deliver him; I will set him securely on high, because he has known My name.',
        15: 'He will call upon Me, and I will answer him; I will be with him in trouble; I will rescue him and honor him.',
        16: 'With long life I will satisfy him and let him see My salvation."',
    },
    92: {  # Psalm 92 — A Psalm, a Song for the Sabbath day. 16 verses.
        1: 'A Psalm, a Song for the Sabbath day.',
        2: 'It is good to give thanks to the LORD and to sing praises to Your name, O Most High;',
        3: 'to declare Your lovingkindness in the morning and Your faithfulness by night,',
        4: 'with the ten-stringed lute and with the harp, with resounding music upon the lyre.',
        5: 'For You, O LORD, have made me glad by what You have done; I will sing for joy at the works of Your hands.',
        6: 'How great are Your works, O LORD! Your thoughts are very deep.',
        7: 'A senseless man has no knowledge, nor does a fool understand this:',
        8: 'that when the wicked sprouted up like grass and all who did iniquity flourished, it was only that they might be destroyed forevermore.',
        9: 'But You, O LORD, are on high forever.',
        10: 'For behold, Your enemies, O LORD, for behold, Your enemies will perish; all who do iniquity will be scattered.',
        11: 'But You have exalted my horn like that of the wild ox; I have been anointed with fresh oil.',
        12: 'And my eye has looked exultantly upon my foes; my ears hear of the evildoers who rise up against me.',
        13: 'The righteous man will flourish like the palm tree; he will grow like a cedar in Lebanon.',
        14: 'Planted in the house of the LORD, they will flourish in the courts of our God.',
        15: 'They will still yield fruit in old age; they shall be full of sap and very green,',
        16: 'to declare that the LORD is upright; He is my rock, and there is no unrighteousness in Him.',
    },
    93: {  # Psalm 93 — The LORD reigns. 5 verses.
        1: 'The LORD reigns, He is clothed with majesty; the LORD has clothed and girded Himself with strength; indeed, the world is firmly established, it will not be moved.',
        2: 'Your throne is established from of old; You are from everlasting.',
        3: 'The floods have lifted up, O LORD, the floods have lifted up their voice; the floods lift up their pounding waves.',
        4: 'More than the sounds of many waters, than the mighty breakers of the sea, the LORD on high is mighty.',
        5: 'Your testimonies are fully confirmed; holiness befits Your house, O LORD, forevermore.',
    },
    94: {  # Psalm 94 — God of vengeance. 23 verses.
        1: 'O LORD, God of vengeance, God of vengeance, shine forth!',
        2: 'Rise up, O Judge of the earth; render recompense to the proud.',
        3: 'How long shall the wicked, O LORD, how long shall the wicked exult?',
        4: 'They pour forth words, they speak arrogantly; all who do wickedness vaunt themselves.',
        5: 'They crush Your people, O LORD, and afflict Your heritage.',
        6: 'They slay the widow and the stranger and murder the orphans.',
        7: 'They have said, "The LORD does not see, nor does the God of Jacob pay heed."',
        8: 'Pay heed, you senseless among the people; and when will you understand, O fools?',
        9: 'He who planted the ear, does He not hear? He who formed the eye, does He not see?',
        10: 'He who chastens the nations, will He not rebuke, even He who teaches man knowledge?',
        11: 'The LORD knows the thoughts of man, that they are a mere breath.',
        12: 'Blessed is the man whom You chasten, O LORD, and whom You teach out of Your law;',
        13: 'that You may grant him relief from the days of adversity, until a pit is dug for the wicked.',
        14: 'For the LORD will not abandon His people, nor will He forsake His inheritance.',
        15: 'For judgment will again be righteous, and all the upright in heart will follow it.',
        16: 'Who will stand up for me against evildoers? Who will take his stand for me against those who do wickedness?',
        17: 'If the LORD had not been my help, my soul would soon have dwelt in the abode of silence.',
        18: 'If I should say, "My foot has slipped," Your lovingkindness, O LORD, will hold me up.',
        19: 'When my anxious thoughts multiply within me, Your consolations delight my soul.',
        20: 'Can a throne of destruction be allied with You, one which devises mischief by decree?',
        21: 'They band themselves together against the soul of the righteous and condemn the innocent to death.',
        22: 'But the LORD has been my stronghold, and my God the rock of my refuge.',
        23: 'He has brought back their wickedness upon them and will destroy them in their evil; the LORD our God will destroy them.',
    },
    95: {  # Psalm 95 — Come, let us worship. 11 verses.
        1: 'O come, let us sing for joy to the LORD; let us shout joyfully to the rock of our salvation.',
        2: 'Let us come before His presence with thanksgiving; let us shout joyfully to Him with psalms.',
        3: 'For the LORD is a great God and a great King above all gods.',
        4: 'In His hand are the depths of the earth; the peaks of the mountains are His also.',
        5: 'The sea is His, for it was He who made it, and His hands formed the dry land.',
        6: 'Come, let us worship and bow down; let us kneel before the LORD our Maker.',
        7: 'For He is our God, and we are the people of His pasture and the sheep of His hand. Today, if you would hear His voice,',
        8: 'do not harden your hearts, as at Meribah, as in the day of Massah in the wilderness,',
        9: 'when your fathers tested Me; they tried Me, though they had seen My work.',
        10: 'For forty years I loathed that generation, and said they are a people who err in their heart, and they do not know My ways.',
        11: 'Therefore I swore in My anger, truly they shall not enter into My rest.',
    },
    96: {  # Psalm 96 — Sing to the LORD a new song. 13 verses.
        1: 'Sing to the LORD a new song; sing to the LORD, all the earth.',
        2: 'Sing to the LORD, bless His name; proclaim good tidings of His salvation from day to day.',
        3: 'Tell of His glory among the nations, His wonderful deeds among all the peoples.',
        4: 'For great is the LORD and greatly to be praised; He is to be feared above all gods.',
        5: 'For all the gods of the peoples are idols, but the LORD made the heavens.',
        6: 'Splendor and majesty are before Him; strength and beauty are in His sanctuary.',
        7: 'Ascribe to the LORD, O families of the peoples, ascribe to the LORD glory and strength.',
        8: 'Ascribe to the LORD the glory of His name; bring an offering and come into His courts.',
        9: 'Worship the LORD in holy attire; tremble before Him, all the earth.',
        10: 'Say among the nations, "The LORD reigns; indeed, the world is firmly established, it will not be moved; He will judge the peoples with equity."',
        11: 'Let the heavens be glad, and let the earth rejoice; let the sea roar, and all it contains;',
        12: 'let the field exult, and all that is in it. Then all the trees of the forest will sing for joy',
        13: 'before the LORD, for He is coming; for He is coming to judge the earth. He will judge the world in righteousness and the peoples in His faithfulness.',
    },
    97: {  # Psalm 97 — The LORD reigns; let the earth rejoice. 12 verses.
        1: 'The LORD reigns, let the earth rejoice; let the many islands be glad.',
        2: 'Clouds and thick darkness surround Him; righteousness and justice are the foundation of His throne.',
        3: 'Fire goes before Him and burns up His adversaries round about.',
        4: 'His lightnings lit up the world; the earth saw and trembled.',
        5: 'The mountains melted like wax at the presence of the LORD, at the presence of the Lord of the whole earth.',
        6: 'The heavens declare His righteousness, and all the peoples have seen His glory.',
        7: 'Let all those be ashamed who serve graven images, who boast themselves of idols; worship Him, all you gods.',
        8: 'Zion heard this and was glad, and the daughters of Judah have rejoiced because of Your judgments, O LORD.',
        9: 'For You are the LORD Most High over all the earth; You are exalted far above all gods.',
        10: 'Hate evil, you who love the LORD, who preserves the souls of His godly ones; He delivers them from the hand of the wicked.',
        11: 'Light is sown like seed for the righteous and gladness for the upright in heart.',
        12: 'Be glad in the LORD, you righteous ones, and give thanks to His holy name.',
    },
    98: {  # Psalm 98 — A Psalm. Sing a new song. 9 verses.
        1: 'A Psalm. O sing to the LORD a new song, for He has done wonderful things; His right hand and His holy arm have gained the victory for Him.',
        2: 'The LORD has made known His salvation; He has revealed His righteousness in the sight of the nations.',
        3: 'He has remembered His lovingkindness and His faithfulness to the house of Israel; all the ends of the earth have seen the salvation of our God.',
        4: 'Shout joyfully to the LORD, all the earth; break forth and sing for joy and sing praises.',
        5: 'Sing praises to the LORD with the lyre, with the lyre and the sound of melody.',
        6: 'With trumpets and the sound of the horn shout joyfully before the King, the LORD.',
        7: 'Let the sea roar and all it contains, the world and those who dwell in it.',
        8: 'Let the rivers clap their hands; let the mountains sing together for joy',
        9: 'before the LORD, for He is coming to judge the earth; He will judge the world with righteousness and the peoples with equity.',
    },
    99: {  # Psalm 99 — The LORD reigns, let the peoples tremble. 9 verses.
        1: 'The LORD reigns, let the peoples tremble; He is enthroned above the cherubim, let the earth shake!',
        2: 'The LORD is great in Zion, and He is exalted above all the peoples.',
        3: 'Let them praise Your great and awesome name; holy is He.',
        4: 'The strength of the King loves justice; You have established equity; You have executed justice and righteousness in Jacob.',
        5: 'Exalt the LORD our God and worship at His footstool; holy is He.',
        6: 'Moses and Aaron were among His priests, and Samuel was among those who called on His name; they called upon the LORD and He answered them.',
        7: 'He spoke to them in the pillar of cloud; they kept His testimonies and the statute that He gave them.',
        8: 'O LORD our God, You answered them; You were a forgiving God to them, and yet an avenger of their evil deeds.',
        9: 'Exalt the LORD our God and worship at His holy hill, for holy is the LORD our God.',
    },
    100: {  # Psalm 100 — A Psalm for Thanksgiving. 5 verses.
        1: 'A Psalm for Thanksgiving. Shout joyfully to the LORD, all the earth.',
        2: 'Serve the LORD with gladness; come before Him with joyful singing.',
        3: 'Know that the LORD Himself is God; it is He who has made us, and not we ourselves; we are His people and the sheep of His pasture.',
        4: 'Enter His gates with thanksgiving and His courts with praise. Give thanks to Him, bless His name.',
        5: 'For the LORD is good; His lovingkindness is everlasting and His faithfulness to all generations.',
    },
    101: {  # Psalm 101 — A Psalm of David. Royal ethics. 8 verses.
        1: 'A Psalm of David. I will sing of lovingkindness and justice; to You, O LORD, I will sing praises.',
        2: 'I will give heed to the blameless way. When will You come to me? I will walk within my house in the integrity of my heart.',
        3: 'I will set no worthless thing before my eyes; I hate the work of those who fall away; it shall not cling to me.',
        4: 'A perverse heart shall depart from me; I will know no evil.',
        5: 'Whoever secretly slanders his neighbor, him I will destroy; no one who has a haughty look and an arrogant heart will I endure.',
        6: 'My eyes shall be upon the faithful of the land, that they may dwell with me; he who walks in a blameless way is the one who will minister to me.',
        7: 'He who practices deceit shall not dwell within my house; he who speaks falsehood shall not maintain his position before me.',
        8: 'Every morning I will destroy all the wicked of the land, so as to cut off from the city of the LORD all those who do iniquity.',
    },
    102: {  # Psalm 102 — Prayer of the afflicted. 29 verses.
        1: 'A Prayer of the afflicted when he is faint and pours out his complaint before the LORD.',
        2: 'Hear my prayer, O LORD, and let my cry for help come to You.',
        3: 'Do not hide Your face from me in the day of my distress; incline Your ear to me; in the day when I call answer me quickly.',
        4: 'For my days have been consumed in smoke, and my bones have been scorched like a hearth.',
        5: 'My heart has been smitten like grass and has withered away; indeed, I forget to eat my bread.',
        6: 'Because of the loudness of my groaning my bones cling to my flesh.',
        7: 'I resemble a pelican of the wilderness; I have become like an owl of the waste places.',
        8: 'I lie awake; I have become like a lonely bird on a housetop.',
        9: 'My enemies have reproached me all day long; those who deride me have used my name as a curse.',
        10: 'For I have eaten ashes like bread and mingled my drink with weeping,',
        11: 'because of Your indignation and Your wrath, for You have lifted me up and cast me away.',
        12: 'My days are like a lengthened shadow, and I wither away like grass.',
        13: 'But You, O LORD, abide forever, and Your name to all generations.',
        14: 'You will arise and have compassion on Zion; for it is time to be gracious to her, for the appointed time has come.',
        15: 'Surely Your servants find pleasure in her stones and feel pity for her dust.',
        16: 'So the nations will fear the name of the LORD and all the kings of the earth Your glory.',
        17: 'For the LORD has built up Zion; He has appeared in His glory.',
        18: 'He has regarded the prayer of the destitute and has not despised their prayer.',
        19: 'This will be written for the generation to come, that a people yet to be created may praise the LORD.',
        20: 'For He looked down from His holy height; from heaven the LORD gazed upon the earth,',
        21: 'to hear the groaning of the prisoner, to set free those who were doomed to death,',
        22: 'that men may tell of the name of the LORD in Zion and His praise in Jerusalem,',
        23: 'when the peoples are gathered together, and the kingdoms, to serve the LORD.',
        24: 'He has weakened my strength in the way; He has shortened my days.',
        25: 'I say, "O my God, do not take me away in the midst of my days, Your years are throughout all generations.',
        26: 'Of old You founded the earth, and the heavens are the work of Your hands.',
        27: 'Even they will perish, but You endure; and all of them will wear out like a garment; like clothing You will change them and they will be changed.',
        28: 'But You are the same, and Your years will not come to an end.',
        29: 'The children of Your servants will continue, and their descendants will be established before You."',
    },
    103: {  # Psalm 103 — Of David. Bless the LORD, O my soul. 22 verses.
        1: 'Of David. Bless the LORD, O my soul, and all that is within me, bless His holy name.',
        2: 'Bless the LORD, O my soul, and forget none of His benefits;',
        3: 'who pardons all your iniquities, who heals all your diseases;',
        4: 'who redeems your life from the pit, who crowns you with lovingkindness and compassion;',
        5: 'who satisfies your years with good things, so that your youth is renewed like the eagle.',
        6: 'The LORD performs righteous deeds and judgments for all who are oppressed.',
        7: 'He made known His ways to Moses, His acts to the sons of Israel.',
        8: 'The LORD is compassionate and gracious, slow to anger and abounding in lovingkindness.',
        9: 'He will not always strive with us, nor will He keep His anger forever.',
        10: 'He has not dealt with us according to our sins, nor rewarded us according to our iniquities.',
        11: 'For as high as the heavens are above the earth, so great is His lovingkindness toward those who fear Him.',
        12: 'As far as the east is from the west, so far has He removed our transgressions from us.',
        13: 'Just as a father has compassion on his children, so the LORD has compassion on those who fear Him.',
        14: 'For He Himself knows our frame; He is mindful that we are but dust.',
        15: 'As for man, his days are like grass; as a flower of the field, so he flourishes.',
        16: 'When the wind has passed over it, it is no more, and its place acknowledges it no longer.',
        17: 'But the lovingkindness of the LORD is from everlasting to everlasting on those who fear Him, and His righteousness to children\'s children,',
        18: 'to those who keep His covenant and remember His precepts to do them.',
        19: 'The LORD has established His throne in the heavens, and His sovereignty rules over all.',
        20: 'Bless the LORD, you His angels, mighty in strength, who perform His word, obeying the voice of His word!',
        21: 'Bless the LORD, all you His hosts, you who serve Him, doing His will.',
        22: 'Bless the LORD, all you works of His, in all places of His dominion; bless the LORD, O my soul!',
    },
    104: {  # Psalm 104 — The creation psalm. 35 verses.
        1: 'Bless the LORD, O my soul! O LORD my God, You are very great; You are clothed with splendor and majesty,',
        2: 'covering Yourself with light as with a cloak, stretching out heaven like a tent curtain.',
        3: 'He lays the beams of His upper chambers in the waters; He makes the clouds His chariot; He walks upon the wings of the wind;',
        4: 'He makes the winds His messengers, flaming fire His ministers.',
        5: 'He established the earth upon its foundations, so that it will not totter forever and ever.',
        6: 'You covered it with the deep as with a garment; the waters were standing above the mountains.',
        7: 'At Your rebuke they fled; at the sound of Your thunder they hurried away.',
        8: 'The mountains rose; the valleys sank down to the place which You established for them.',
        9: 'You set a boundary that they may not pass over, so that they will not return to cover the earth.',
        10: 'He sends forth springs in the valleys; they flow between the mountains;',
        11: 'they give drink to every beast of the field; the wild donkeys quench their thirst.',
        12: 'Beside them the birds of the heavens dwell; they lift up their voices among the branches.',
        13: 'He waters the mountains from His upper chambers; the earth is satisfied with the fruit of His works.',
        14: 'He causes the grass to grow for the cattle, and vegetation for the labor of man, so that he may bring forth food from the earth,',
        15: 'and wine which makes man\'s heart glad, so that he may make his face glisten with oil, and food which sustains man\'s heart.',
        16: 'The trees of the LORD drink their fill, the cedars of Lebanon which He planted,',
        17: 'where the birds build their nests; the stork, whose home is the fir trees.',
        18: 'The high mountains are for the wild goats; the cliffs are a refuge for the rock badgers.',
        19: 'He made the moon for the seasons; the sun knows the place of its setting.',
        20: 'You appoint darkness and it becomes night, in which all the beasts of the forest prowl about.',
        21: 'The young lions roar after their prey and seek their food from God.',
        22: 'When the sun rises they withdraw and lie down in their dens.',
        23: 'Man goes forth to his work and to his labor until evening.',
        24: 'O LORD, how many are Your works! In wisdom You have made them all; the earth is full of Your possessions.',
        25: 'There is the sea, great and broad, in which are swarms without number, animals both small and great.',
        26: 'There the ships move along, and Leviathan, which You have formed to sport in it.',
        27: 'They all wait for You to give them their food in due season.',
        28: 'You give to them, they gather it up; You open Your hand, they are satisfied with good.',
        29: 'You hide Your face, they are dismayed; You take away their spirit, they expire and return to their dust.',
        30: 'You send forth Your Spirit, they are created; and You renew the face of the ground.',
        31: 'Let the glory of the LORD endure forever; let the LORD be glad in His works;',
        32: 'He looks at the earth, and it trembles; He touches the mountains, and they smoke.',
        33: 'I will sing to the LORD as long as I live; I will sing praise to my God while I have my being.',
        34: 'Let my meditation be pleasing to Him; as for me, I shall be glad in the LORD.',
        35: 'Let sinners be consumed from the earth and let the wicked be no more. Bless the LORD, O my soul. Praise the LORD!',
    },
    105: {  # Psalm 105 — God's faithfulness to Abraham's covenant. 45 verses.
        1: 'Oh give thanks to the LORD, call upon His name; make known His deeds among the peoples.',
        2: 'Sing to Him, sing praises to Him; speak of all His wonders.',
        3: 'Glory in His holy name; let the heart of those who seek the LORD be glad.',
        4: 'Seek the LORD and His strength; seek His face continually.',
        5: 'Remember His wonders which He has done, His marvels and the judgments uttered by His mouth,',
        6: 'O seed of Abraham, His servant, O sons of Jacob, His chosen ones!',
        7: 'He is the LORD our God; His judgments are in all the earth.',
        8: 'He has remembered His covenant forever, the word which He commanded to a thousand generations,',
        9: 'the covenant which He made with Abraham, and His oath to Isaac.',
        10: 'Then He confirmed it to Jacob for a statute, to Israel as an everlasting covenant,',
        11: 'saying, "To you I will give the land of Canaan as the portion of your inheritance,"',
        12: 'when they were only a few men in number, very few, and strangers in it.',
        13: 'And they wandered about from nation to nation, from one kingdom to another people.',
        14: 'He permitted no man to oppress them, and He reproved kings for their sakes:',
        15: '"Do not touch My anointed ones, and do My prophets no harm."',
        16: 'And He called for a famine upon the land; He broke the whole staff of bread.',
        17: 'He sent a man before them, Joseph, who was sold as a slave.',
        18: 'They afflicted his feet with fetters; he himself was laid in irons,',
        19: 'until the time that his word came to pass, the word of the LORD tested him.',
        20: 'The king sent and released him, the ruler of peoples, and set him free.',
        21: 'He made him lord of his house and ruler over all his possessions,',
        22: 'to imprison his princes at will, that he might teach his elders wisdom.',
        23: 'Israel also came into Egypt; thus Jacob sojourned in the land of Ham.',
        24: 'And He caused His people to be very fruitful, and made them stronger than their adversaries.',
        25: 'He turned their heart to hate His people, to deal craftily with His servants.',
        26: 'He sent Moses His servant, and Aaron whom He had chosen.',
        27: 'They performed His wondrous acts among them, and miracles in the land of Ham.',
        28: 'He sent darkness and made it dark; and they did not rebel against His words.',
        29: 'He turned their waters into blood and caused their fish to die.',
        30: 'Their land swarmed with frogs even in the chambers of their kings.',
        31: 'He spoke, and there came a swarm of flies and gnats in all their territory.',
        32: 'He gave them hail for rain, and flaming fire in their land.',
        33: 'He struck down their vines also and their fig trees, and shattered the trees of their territory.',
        34: 'He spoke, and locusts came, and young locusts, even without number,',
        35: 'and ate up all vegetation in their land, and ate up the fruit of their ground.',
        36: 'He also struck down all the firstborn in their land, the first fruits of all their vigor.',
        37: 'Then He brought them out with silver and gold, and among His tribes there was not one who stumbled.',
        38: 'Egypt was glad when they departed, for the dread of them had fallen upon them.',
        39: 'He spread a cloud for a covering, and fire to illumine by night.',
        40: 'They asked, and He brought quail, and satisfied them with the bread of heaven.',
        41: 'He opened the rock and water flowed out; it ran in the dry places like a river.',
        42: 'For He remembered His holy word with Abraham His servant;',
        43: 'and He brought forth His people with joy, His chosen ones with a joyful shout.',
        44: 'He gave them also the lands of the nations, that they might take possession of the fruit of the peoples\' labor,',
        45: 'so that they might keep His statutes and observe His laws. Praise the LORD!',
    },
    106: {  # Psalm 106 — Israel's rebellion despite God's faithfulness. 48 verses.
        1: 'Praise the LORD! Oh give thanks to the LORD, for He is good; for His lovingkindness is everlasting.',
        2: 'Who can speak of the mighty deeds of the LORD, or can show forth all His praise?',
        3: 'How blessed are those who keep justice, who practice righteousness at all times!',
        4: 'Remember me, O LORD, in Your favor toward Your people; visit me with Your salvation,',
        5: 'that I may see the prosperity of Your chosen ones, that I may rejoice in the gladness of Your nation, that I may glory with Your inheritance.',
        6: 'We have sinned like our fathers; we have committed iniquity; we have behaved wickedly.',
        7: 'Our fathers in Egypt did not understand Your wonders; they did not remember Your abundant kindnesses, but rebelled by the sea, at the Red Sea.',
        8: 'Nevertheless He saved them for the sake of His name, that He might make His power known.',
        9: 'Thus He rebuked the Red Sea and it dried up, and He led them through the deeps, as through the wilderness.',
        10: 'So He saved them from the hand of the one who hated them, and redeemed them from the hand of the enemy.',
        11: 'The waters covered their adversaries; not one of them was left.',
        12: 'Then they believed His words; they sang His praise.',
        13: 'They quickly forgot His works; they did not wait for His counsel,',
        14: 'but craved intensely in the wilderness, and tempted God in the desert.',
        15: 'So He gave them their request, but sent a wasting disease among them.',
        16: 'When they became envious of Moses in the camp, and of Aaron, the holy one of the LORD,',
        17: 'the earth opened and swallowed up Dathan, and engulfed the company of Abiram.',
        18: 'And a fire blazed up in their company; the flame consumed the wicked.',
        19: 'They made a calf in Horeb and worshiped a molten image.',
        20: 'Thus they exchanged their glory for the image of an ox that eats grass.',
        21: 'They forgot God their Savior, who had done great things in Egypt,',
        22: 'wonders in the land of Ham and awesome things by the Red Sea.',
        23: 'Therefore He said that He would destroy them, had not Moses His chosen one stood in the breach before Him, to turn away His wrath from destroying them.',
        24: 'Then they despised the pleasant land; they did not believe in His word,',
        25: 'but grumbled in their tents; they did not listen to the voice of the LORD.',
        26: 'Therefore He swore to them that He would cast them down in the wilderness,',
        27: 'and that He would cast their seed among the nations and scatter them in the lands.',
        28: 'They joined themselves also to Baal-peor, and ate sacrifices offered to the dead.',
        29: 'Thus they provoked Him to anger with their deeds, and the plague broke out among them.',
        30: 'Then Phinehas stood up and interposed, and so the plague was stayed.',
        31: 'And it was reckoned to him for righteousness, to all generations forever.',
        32: 'They also provoked Him to wrath at the waters of Meribah, so that it went ill with Moses on their account;',
        33: 'because they were rebellious against His Spirit, he spoke rashly with his lips.',
        34: 'They did not destroy the peoples, as the LORD commanded them,',
        35: 'but they mingled with the nations and learned their practices,',
        36: 'and served their idols, which became a snare to them.',
        37: 'They even sacrificed their sons and their daughters to the demons,',
        38: 'and shed innocent blood, the blood of their sons and their daughters, whom they sacrificed to the idols of Canaan; and the land was polluted with the blood.',
        39: 'Thus they became unclean in their practices, and played the harlot in their deeds.',
        40: 'Therefore the anger of the LORD was kindled against His people and He abhorred His inheritance.',
        41: 'Then He gave them into the hand of the nations, and those who hated them ruled over them.',
        42: 'Their enemies also oppressed them, and they were subdued under their hand.',
        43: 'Many times He would deliver them; they, however, were rebellious in their counsel, and so sank down in their iniquity.',
        44: 'Nevertheless He looked upon their distress when He heard their cry;',
        45: 'and He remembered His covenant for their sake, and relented according to the greatness of His lovingkindness.',
        46: 'He also made them objects of compassion in the presence of all their captors.',
        47: 'Save us, O LORD our God, and gather us from among the nations, to give thanks to Your holy name and glory in Your praise.',
        48: 'Blessed be the LORD, the God of Israel, from everlasting even to everlasting. And let all the people say, "Amen." Praise the LORD!',
    },
    107: {  # Psalm 107 — Give thanks to the LORD for His lovingkindness. 43 verses.
        1: 'Oh give thanks to the LORD, for He is good, for His lovingkindness is everlasting.',
        2: 'Let the redeemed of the LORD say so, whom He has redeemed from the hand of the adversary',
        3: 'and gathered from the lands, from the east and from the west, from the north and from the south.',
        4: 'They wandered in the wilderness in a desert region; they did not find a way to an inhabited city.',
        5: 'They were hungry and thirsty; their soul fainted within them.',
        6: 'Then they cried out to the LORD in their trouble; He delivered them out of their distresses.',
        7: 'He led them also by a straight way, to go to an inhabited city.',
        8: 'Let them give thanks to the LORD for His lovingkindness, and for His wonders to the sons of men!',
        9: 'For He has satisfied the thirsty soul, and the hungry soul He has filled with what is good.',
        10: 'There were those who dwelt in darkness and in the shadow of death, prisoners in misery and chains,',
        11: 'because they had rebelled against the words of God and spurned the counsel of the Most High.',
        12: 'Therefore He humbled their heart with labor; they stumbled and there was none to help.',
        13: 'Then they cried out to the LORD in their trouble; He saved them out of their distresses.',
        14: 'He brought them out of darkness and the shadow of death and broke their bands apart.',
        15: 'Let them give thanks to the LORD for His lovingkindness, and for His wonders to the sons of men!',
        16: 'For He has shattered gates of bronze and cut bars of iron asunder.',
        17: 'Fools, because of their rebellious way, and because of their iniquities, were afflicted.',
        18: 'Their soul abhorred all kinds of food, and they drew near to the gates of death.',
        19: 'Then they cried out to the LORD in their trouble; He saved them out of their distresses.',
        20: 'He sent His word and healed them, and delivered them from their destructions.',
        21: 'Let them give thanks to the LORD for His lovingkindness, and for His wonders to the sons of men!',
        22: 'Let them also offer sacrifices of thanksgiving, and tell of His works with joyful singing.',
        23: 'Those who go down to the sea in ships, who do business on great waters;',
        24: 'they have seen the works of the LORD, and His wonders in the deep.',
        25: 'For He spoke and raised up a stormy wind, which lifted up the waves of the sea.',
        26: 'They rose up to the heavens, they went down to the depths; their soul melted away in their misery.',
        27: 'They reeled and staggered like a drunken man, and were at their wits\' end.',
        28: 'Then they cried to the LORD in their trouble, and He brought them out of their distresses.',
        29: 'He caused the storm to be still, so that the waves of the sea were hushed.',
        30: 'Then they were glad because they were quiet, and He guided them to their desired haven.',
        31: 'Let them give thanks to the LORD for His lovingkindness, and for His wonders to the sons of men!',
        32: 'Let them extol Him also in the congregation of the people, and praise Him at the seat of the elders.',
        33: 'He changes rivers into a wilderness and springs of water into a thirsty ground;',
        34: 'a fruitful land into a salt waste, because of the wickedness of those who dwell in it.',
        35: 'He changes a wilderness into a pool of water and a dry land into springs of water;',
        36: 'and there He makes the hungry to dwell, so that they may establish an inhabited city,',
        37: 'and sow fields and plant vineyards, and gather a fruitful harvest.',
        38: 'Also He blesses them and they multiply greatly, and He does not let their cattle decrease.',
        39: 'When they are diminished and bowed down through oppression, misery, and sorrow,',
        40: 'He pours contempt upon princes and makes them wander in a pathless waste.',
        41: 'But He sets the needy securely on high away from affliction, and makes his families like a flock.',
        42: 'The upright see it and are glad; but all unrighteousness shuts its mouth.',
        43: 'Who is wise? Let him give heed to these things, and consider the lovingkindnesses of the LORD.',
    },
    108: {  # Psalm 108 — A Song, a Psalm of David. 14 verses.
        1: 'A Song, a Psalm of David.',
        2: 'My heart is steadfast, O God; I will sing, I will sing praises, even with my glory.',
        3: 'Awake, harp and lyre; I will awaken the dawn!',
        4: 'I will give thanks to You, O LORD, among the peoples, and I will sing praises to You among the nations.',
        5: 'For Your lovingkindness is great above the heavens, and Your truth reaches to the skies.',
        6: 'Be exalted, O God, above the heavens, and Your glory above all the earth.',
        7: 'That Your beloved may be delivered, save with Your right hand, and answer me!',
        8: 'God has spoken in His holiness: "I will exult, I will portion out Shechem and measure out the valley of Succoth.',
        9: 'Gilead is Mine, Manasseh is Mine; Ephraim also is the helmet of My head; Judah is My scepter.',
        10: 'Moab is My washbowl; over Edom I shall throw My shoe; over Philistia I will shout aloud."',
        11: 'Who will bring me into the besieged city? Who will lead me to Edom?',
        12: 'Have not You Yourself, O God, rejected us? And will You not go forth with our armies, O God?',
        13: 'Oh give us help against the adversary, for deliverance by man is in vain.',
        14: 'Through God we shall do valiantly, and it is He who will tread down our adversaries.',
    },
    109: {  # Psalm 109 — For the choir director. A Psalm of David. Imprecatory. 31 verses.
        1: 'For the choir director. A Psalm of David. O God of my praise, do not be silent!',
        2: 'For they have opened the wicked and deceitful mouth against me; they have spoken against me with a lying tongue.',
        3: 'They have also surrounded me with words of hatred, and fought against me without cause.',
        4: 'In return for my love they act as my accusers; but I am in prayer.',
        5: 'Thus they have repaid me evil for good and hatred for my love.',
        6: '"Appoint a wicked man over him, and let an accuser stand at his right hand.',
        7: 'When he is judged, let him come forth guilty, and let his prayer become sin.',
        8: 'Let his days be few; let another take his office.',
        9: 'Let his children be fatherless and his wife a widow.',
        10: 'Let his children wander about and beg; let them seek sustenance far from their ruined homes.',
        11: 'Let the creditor seize all that he has, and let strangers plunder the product of his labor.',
        12: 'Let there be none to extend lovingkindness to him, nor any to be gracious to his fatherless children.',
        13: 'Let his posterity be cut off; in a following generation let their name be blotted out.',
        14: 'Let the iniquity of his fathers be remembered before the LORD, and do not let the sin of his mother be blotted out.',
        15: 'Let them be before the LORD continually, that He may cut off their memory from the earth;',
        16: 'because he did not remember to show lovingkindness, but persecuted the afflicted and needy man, and the despondent in heart, to put them to death.',
        17: 'He also loved cursing, so it came to him; and he did not delight in blessing, so it was far from him.',
        18: 'But he clothed himself with cursing as with his garment, and it entered into his body like water and like oil into his bones.',
        19: 'Let it be to him as a garment with which he covers himself, and for a belt with which he constantly girds himself."',
        20: 'Let this be the reward of my accusers from the LORD, and of those who speak evil against my soul.',
        21: 'But You, O GOD, the Lord, deal kindly with me for Your name\'s sake; because Your lovingkindness is good, deliver me;',
        22: 'for I am afflicted and needy, and my heart is wounded within me.',
        23: 'I am passing like a shadow when it lengthens; I am shaken off like the locust.',
        24: 'My knees are weak from fasting, and my flesh has grown lean, without fatness.',
        25: 'I also have become a reproach to them; when they see me, they wag their head.',
        26: 'Help me, O LORD my God; save me according to Your lovingkindness.',
        27: 'And let them know that this is Your hand; You, LORD, have done it.',
        28: 'Let them curse, but You bless; when they arise, they shall be ashamed, but Your servant shall be glad.',
        29: 'Let my accusers be clothed with dishonor, and let them cover themselves with their own shame as with a robe.',
        30: 'With my mouth I will give thanks abundantly to the LORD; and in the midst of many I will praise Him.',
        31: 'For He stands at the right hand of the needy, to save him from those who judge his soul.',
    },
    110: {  # Psalm 110 — THE MOST-QUOTED PSALM IN THE NT. A Psalm of David. 7 verses.
        1: 'A Psalm of David. The LORD says to my Lord: "Sit at My right hand until I make Your enemies a footstool for Your feet."',
        2: 'The LORD will stretch forth Your strong scepter from Zion, saying, "Rule in the midst of Your enemies."',
        3: 'Your people will volunteer freely in the day of Your power; in holy array, from the womb of the dawn, Your youth are to You as the dew.',
        4: 'The LORD has sworn and will not change His mind, "You are a priest forever according to the order of Melchizedek."',
        5: 'The Lord is at Your right hand; He will shatter kings in the day of His wrath.',
        6: 'He will judge among the nations; He will fill them with corpses; He will shatter the chief men over a broad country.',
        7: 'He will drink from the brook by the wayside; therefore He will lift up His head.',
    },
}

NOTES_PSALMS_73_110 = {
    73: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Surely God is good to Israel" (\'akh tov leyisra\'el Elohim) — the word \'akh ("surely, only") sets up the psalm\'s tension. Asaph\'s conclusion comes first: God IS good. But the journey to that conclusion nearly destroyed him (vv.2-16). "Pure in heart" (barey levav) echoes the Beatitude of Matt. 5:8.',
        3: 'HEBREW: "The prosperity of the wicked" (shalom resha\'im) — shalom here means completeness, wholeness, material well-being. The wicked appear to have the very peace that should belong to the righteous. This is the ancient and persistent problem of theodicy (cf. Job; Jer. 12:1; Hab. 1:13).',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: "How does God know? And is there knowledge with the Most High?" — the wicked deny divine omniscience. If God does not see, there is no accountability. This practical atheism (not denying God\'s existence but denying His awareness) is the foundation of all sin (cf. Ps. 10:11; 94:7; Ezek. 8:12).',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Until I came into the sanctuary of God" (\'ad \'avo \'el miqdeshey-El) — the turning point of the psalm. The problem of the wicked\'s prosperity is not solved by philosophy but by worship. In God\'s presence, Asaph gains an eternal perspective that earthly observation could not provide. This is the psalmic answer to the problem of theodicy.',
        23: 'HEBREW: "Nevertheless I am continually with You" (wa\'ani tamid \'immakh) — despite his near-fall, Asaph was never actually separated from God. This is one of the most profound statements of divine preservation in the Psalter. God held his right hand even when he did not know it.',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: "And afterward receive me to glory" (we\'achar kavod tiqqacheni) — the verb laqach (take, receive) is the same used for Enoch\'s translation (Gen. 5:24) and Elijah\'s ascent (2 Kings 2:3, 9). Asaph glimpses a destiny beyond death — afterlife hope emerging within the Psalter.',
        25: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Whom have I in heaven but You?" (mi li vashamayim) — Asaph\'s ultimate conclusion transcends the original question. The prosperity of the wicked becomes irrelevant. God Himself — not His gifts — is the psalmist\'s portion (cheleq, v.26). This is the summit of Old Testament devotion.',
    },
    74: {
        1: 'HEBREW: Maskil — a wisdom or instruction psalm. "Why have You rejected us forever?" (lamah zanachta lanetsach) — the strongest communal lament language. The destruction of the Temple (vv.3-8) is described in vivid, devastating detail.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "We do not see our signs; there is no longer any prophet" — the absence of prophetic voice compounds the crisis. Signs (\'otot) confirmed God\'s presence; prophets mediated His word. Without either, the community faces existential darkness. This describes the post-exilic or inter-testamental silence.',
        13: 'HEBREW: "You divided the sea" (\'attah phorrarta veyam) — the Exodus language shifts to creation mythology. "Sea monsters" (tanninim) and "Leviathan" (v.14) represent chaos forces that God subdued at creation and at the Red Sea. This combat myth imagery (sometimes called chaoskampf) affirms God\'s sovereign power over all forces of chaos and evil.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: "You crushed the heads of Leviathan" — Leviathan here represents the multi-headed chaos serpent known throughout ancient Near Eastern mythology (cf. Ugaritic Litanu). The psalmist appeals to God\'s original victory over chaos as grounds for a new act of deliverance. If God conquered Leviathan, He can surely defeat Israel\'s earthly enemies.',
        20: 'HEBREW: "Have regard for the covenant" (habbet labberit) — the covenant is Israel\'s ultimate ground of appeal. God bound Himself by covenant, and the psalmist holds Him to it. This is not presumption but faith — trusting that God\'s own character compels Him to act.',
    },
    75: {
        3: 'HEBREW: "When I select an appointed time" (ki \'eqqach mo\'ed) — God speaks in first person. Mo\'ed means appointed time, festival, set meeting. God alone determines the timing of judgment. Human impatience must yield to divine scheduling.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Not from the east, nor from the west, nor from the desert comes exaltation" — no geographic source or human agency can elevate a person. Only God lifts up and puts down. The fourfold negation (east, west, south/desert — with north omitted because that is God\'s dwelling in Canaanite cosmology) leaves God as the sole source of authority.',
        8: 'HEBREW: "A cup is in the hand of the LORD" (kos beyad-YHWH) — the cup of divine wrath is a recurring prophetic image (Isa. 51:17; Jer. 25:15-16; Rev. 14:10). The wicked must drain it to the dregs (shemarim, the sediment at the bottom). God\'s judgment is thorough and complete.',
    },
    76: {
        2: 'HEBREW: "Salem" (Shalem) — an ancient name for Jerusalem (Gen. 14:18, where Melchizedek is king of Salem). The connection to Melchizedek anticipates Ps. 110:4. "Zion" (Tsiyyon) is the specific hill of God\'s dwelling. The psalm celebrates God\'s military victory from His holy city.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: "You, even You, are to be feared" (\'attah nora\' \'attah) — the repetition of \'attah ("You") is emphatic. The fear of God is the proper response to His power. "Who may stand in Your presence when once You are angry?" — the answer is: no one (cf. Nah. 1:6; Mal. 3:2; Rev. 6:17).',
        10: 'HEBREW: "The wrath of man shall praise You" (ki chamat \'adam todekka) — one of the most paradoxical statements in the Psalter. Even human rage, directed against God, ultimately serves His glory. God turns the wrath of His enemies into an occasion for His own exaltation (cf. Gen. 50:20; Acts 2:23; 4:27-28).',
    },
    77: {
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: The series of anguished questions (vv.7-9) — "Will the Lord reject forever? Has His lovingkindness ceased? Has His promise come to an end?" — represents the dark night of the soul. These are not rhetorical questions; they are genuine cries of a faith struggling to survive. The psalmist\'s honest wrestling with doubt is itself an act of faith, because it is addressed TO God.',
        11: 'HEBREW: "The right hand of the Most High has changed" (shenot yemin \'Elyon) — this is Asaph\'s crisis point. Has God changed? The Hebrew is ambiguous and debated. Some render it "this is my grief: the years of the right hand of the Most High." Either way, the psalmist fears God has withdrawn His power.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Your way, O God, is holy" (Elohim baqqodesh darkekhah) — or "Your way, O God, is in the sanctuary." The resolution comes through remembrance of God\'s mighty deeds (vv.12-20). Memory of past faithfulness becomes the antidote to present despair. The Exodus is the supreme evidence of God\'s power.',
        17: 'HEBREW: "The waters saw You, O God" (ra\'ukha mayim Elohim) — the Exodus is described in cosmic, mythological terms. The waters themselves are personified as seeing God and trembling. This poetic amplification transforms a historical event into a theophany — a manifestation of God\'s presence that shakes creation.',
        20: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Your way was in the sea and Your paths in the mighty waters, and Your footprints were not known" — God\'s ways are ultimately hidden from human sight. He acts powerfully but invisibly. The sea crossing left no footprints. This is the mystery of divine providence: God is present and active even when His methods are untraceable.',
    },
    78: {
        2: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "I will open my mouth in a parable" (eftechah vemashel pi) — Matthew 13:35 quotes this verse as fulfilled in Jesus\' teaching in parables. The mashal (parable, proverb, wisdom saying) and chidot (riddles, dark sayings) suggest hidden wisdom transmitted across generations.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He established a testimony in Jacob and appointed a law in Israel, which He commanded our fathers that they should make them known to their children" — the trans-generational transmission of faith is commanded, not optional. Each generation bears responsibility for the next. The chain from fathers to children to the "generation to come" (v.6) to "children yet to be born" (v.6) extends indefinitely.',
        24: 'HEBREW: "He rained down manna upon them to eat" (wayyamter \'alehem man le\'ekhol) — manna (man) literally means "What is it?" (Exod. 16:15). Called "the bread of the mighty ones" (lechem \'abbirim, v.25) or "bread of angels" in the LXX. Jesus identifies Himself as the true bread from heaven that the manna typified (John 6:31-35).',
        38: 'THEOLOGICAL: "But He, being compassionate, forgave their iniquity" (wehu\' rachum yechapper \'awon) — the central theological statement of the psalm. Despite Israel\'s relentless rebellion (the entire narrative is a cycle of sin, judgment, and mercy), God\'s compassion prevails. Yechapper uses the root k-p-r (atone, cover), the same root behind Yom Kippur.',
        49: 'HEBREW: "A band of destroying angels" (mishlachat mal\'akhey ra\'im) — literally "a sending of angels of evil." These are divine agents executing God\'s judgment on Egypt. The plagues were not natural disasters but angelic missions. This detail expands the Exodus narrative with the involvement of God\'s heavenly host in earthly judgment.',
        56: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Yet they tempted and rebelled against the Most High God" — the cycle repeats even after entering the promised land (vv.56-64). Possession of the land does not guarantee faithfulness. Israel\'s high places (bamot, v.58) and graven images (pesilim) provoked God\'s jealousy (qin\'ah). The jealousy of God is not petty emotion but the holy passion of a covenant Lord whose people have committed spiritual adultery.',
        60: 'HEBREW: "He abandoned the dwelling place at Shiloh" (wayyittosh mishkan Shiloh) — a devastating statement. God abandoned His own dwelling. Shiloh was the location of the tabernacle from Joshua through Samuel (Josh. 18:1; 1 Sam. 1:3). Its destruction (cf. Jer. 7:12-14) demonstrated that no place is immune from God\'s judgment when His people persist in unfaithfulness.',
        70: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He chose David His servant" (wayyivchar beDavid \'avdo) — the psalm culminates in God\'s choice of David. The rejection of Ephraim/Shiloh (v.67) and the election of Judah/Zion/David (vv.68-72) establish the Davidic covenant as the new center of God\'s purposes. David the shepherd becomes shepherd of God\'s flock — a messianic foreshadowing (Ezek. 34:23; John 10:11).',
    },
    79: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The nations have invaded Your inheritance" (ba\'u goyim benachalatekha) — the land belongs to God (nachalah = inheritance); the nations have violated divine property. The defilement of the Temple, the dead bodies, and blood poured out "like water" paint a scene of total desecration. This likely refers to the Babylonian destruction of 586 BC.',
        5: 'HEBREW: "How long, O LORD?" (\'ad mah YHWH) — the classic lament formula (cf. Pss. 13:1; 74:10; 80:4; 89:46). The combination of anger (\'anaph), jealousy (qin\'ah), and fire (\'esh) describes divine wrath in its fullest intensity.',
        9: 'HEBREW: "For Your name\'s sake" (\'al devar kevod shemekhah) — the appeal is not to Israel\'s merit but to God\'s reputation. This is covenant logic: God\'s name is bound to His people. Their destruction would seem to reflect poorly on Him among the nations (v.10). Moses used the same argument (Num. 14:13-16).',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: "So we Your people and the sheep of Your pasture" — the psalm ends with a vow of perpetual praise. The sheep-shepherd metaphor (cf. Pss. 23:1; 74:1; 78:52; 80:1; 95:7; 100:3) is one of the most persistent images for the God-Israel relationship.',
    },
    80: {
        2: 'HEBREW: "Shepherd of Israel" (ro\'eh Yisra\'el) — God as shepherd is one of the oldest biblical images (Gen. 48:15; 49:24). "Enthroned above the cherubim" (yoshev hakeruvim) — the mercy seat on the Ark of the Covenant, God\'s throne in the Holy of Holies (Exod. 25:22; 1 Sam. 4:4). The cherubim were guardians of divine presence.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Restore us... cause Your face to shine" (hashivenu... ha\'er paneykha) — the refrain of the psalm (vv.4, 8, 20), escalating in divine titles: "O God" (v.4), "O God of hosts" (v.8), "O LORD God of hosts" (v.20). The shining face echoes the Aaronic blessing of Num. 6:25.',
        9: 'HEBREW: "You removed a vine from Egypt" (gephen mimmitsrayim tassia\') — Israel as vine/vineyard is a major biblical metaphor (Isa. 5:1-7; Jer. 2:21; Ezek. 15; 17; Hos. 10:1). Jesus identifies Himself as the "true vine" (John 15:1), implying Israel was the vine that failed its purpose.',
        16: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "The son whom You have strengthened for Yourself" (\'al ben \'immatsah llakh) — or "the son of man" (ben) You have made strong for Yourself. This verse parallels v.18 ("the man of Your right hand, the son of man"). The language anticipates the Son of Man messianic title (Dan. 7:13; used by Jesus in Matt. 26:64).',
        18: 'HEBREW: "The man of Your right hand" (\'ish yeminekha) — combined with "the son of man" (ben \'adam), this double title describes a figure who is both fully human and divinely appointed. The "right hand" position is the place of honor and authority, the same seat offered to the Messiah in Ps. 110:1.',
    },
    81: {
        4: 'HEBREW: "Blow the trumpet at the new moon, at the full moon, on our feast day" (tiq\'u vachodesh shophar bakkese\' leyom chaggenu) — shophar (ram\'s horn) signals sacred time. The "new moon" (chodesh) and "full moon" (kese\') indicate the Feast of Trumpets (Rosh Hashanah, Lev. 23:24) and possibly the Feast of Tabernacles (Lev. 23:34).',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: God speaks directly, recounting the Exodus: "I relieved his shoulder of the burden" (hasiroti missevel shikhmo). The shift to first-person divine speech (vv.7-17) is dramatic. God Himself reviews the relationship, like a plaintiff presenting His case.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: "I, the LORD, am your God, who brought you up from the land of Egypt" (\'anokhi YHWH \'elohekhah hamma\'alkhah me\'erets mitsrayim) — this echoes the prologue to the Ten Commandments (Exod. 20:2). God\'s identity as redeemer grounds His authority to command. "Open your mouth wide and I will fill it" — a stunning image of divine generosity conditioned only on receptivity.',
        14: 'HEBREW: "Oh that My people would listen to Me" (lu \'ammi shomea\' li) — divine pathos. God expresses longing for Israel\'s obedience, not as a tyrant demanding compliance but as a loving Father grieved by His children\'s self-destruction. The conditional "if... I would" structure (vv.14-16) reveals what Israel forfeited through disobedience.',
    },
    82: {
        1: 'DIVINE COUNCIL: "God (Elohim) takes His stand in the congregation of God (El); He judges in the midst of the gods (elohim)" — this is the foundational divine council text. The Hebrew \'adat-El means "the assembly/congregation of El (God)." The term elohim in the final clause refers to divine beings — members of the heavenly court. This is not polytheism but cosmic hierarchy: YHWH is the supreme God who presides over a council of subordinate divine beings (cf. 1 Kings 22:19-22; Job 1:6; 2:1; Isa. 6:1-8; Dan. 7:9-10). The Septuagint renders the final elohim as "gods" (theoi). This assembly is a judicial setting — God rises to render verdict against the corrupt members of His own council.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: God speaks directly to the elohim. Their charge: they have judged unjustly and shown partiality to the wicked. These divine beings were apparently given authority over the nations (cf. Deut. 32:8-9 in the Dead Sea Scrolls reading: "He set the boundaries of the peoples according to the number of the sons of God"). They have failed in their stewardship.',
        5: 'HEBREW: "All the foundations of the earth are shaken" (yimmotu kol mosdey \'arets) — the failure of the divine council members to govern justly has cosmic consequences. Injustice destabilizes creation itself. The "foundations of the earth" represent the moral order that undergirds physical reality.',
        6: 'DIVINE COUNCIL / CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "I said, \'You are gods (elohim), and all of you are sons of the Most High (benei \'Elyon)\'" — God Himself declared these beings to be elohim and benei Elyon. This is the verse Jesus quotes in John 10:34-35 when accused of blasphemy for claiming to be God\'s Son. Jesus\' argument: if Scripture itself calls these lesser beings "gods," how much more appropriate is the title for the one whom the Father sanctified and sent into the world? The verse confirms the existence of a class of divine beings beneath YHWH who hold the title elohim, while simultaneously affirming that they are subordinate and accountable to the Most High.',
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Nevertheless you will die like men (ke\'adam temuton) and fall like one of the princes (kesarim)" — the sentence of mortality is pronounced on immortal beings. These elohim, who were entrusted with governing nations, will be stripped of their divine status and die like humans. This is a demotion and death sentence. The "princes" (sarim) may refer to angelic princes over nations (cf. Dan. 10:13, 20-21 where Michael is the "prince" of Israel). Their judgment anticipates the eschatological judgment of all spiritual powers (1 Cor. 6:3; Rev. 20:10).',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Arise, O God, judge the earth!" (qumah Elohim shophta ha\'arets) — the psalm concludes with a plea for God Himself to take over the judging that the corrupt elohim have botched. Since the subordinate divine beings failed, YHWH must assume direct rule over all nations. This is the eschatological hope: God will reclaim all authority. "For it is You who possesses all the nations" (ki \'attah tinchal bekhol-haggoyim) — all nations belong to God, not to the fallen council members. The psalm moves from divine council corruption to divine reclamation of sovereignty.',
    },
    83: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Do not remain quiet" (\'al demi lakh) — three synonyms for divine silence (demi, quiet; charesh, silent; shaqat, still) intensify the urgency. When God is silent, His enemies interpret it as weakness or absence.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Let us wipe them out as a nation, that the name of Israel be remembered no more" — the most explicit statement of genocidal intent against Israel in the Psalter. The conspiracy of ten nations (vv.6-8) is comprehensive: enemies from every direction. The goal is not merely defeat but annihilation of national identity and memory.',
        6: 'HISTORICAL: The ten-nation coalition: Edom (southeast), Ishmaelites (Arabian desert), Moab (east of Dead Sea), Hagrites (Transjordan nomads), Gebal (Phoenician coast), Ammon (northeast), Amalek (Negev), Philistia (southwest), Tyre (northwest), Assyria (far northeast). This encirclement represents total geopolitical hostility. "Children of Lot" (benei Lot) = Moab and Ammon (Gen. 19:36-38).',
        9: 'HEBREW: The historical precedents invoked — Midian (Judg. 7), Sisera and Jabin (Judg. 4-5), Oreb and Zeeb (Judg. 7:25), Zebah and Zalmunna (Judg. 8:5-21) — are all from the book of Judges. The psalmist asks God to repeat the victories of the past against the coalition of the present.',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Fill their faces with dishonor, that they may seek Your name, O LORD" — the ultimate goal of divine judgment is not annihilation but recognition. Asaph prays for the enemies\' defeat so that they may acknowledge YHWH\'s sovereignty. Even imprecation serves an evangelistic purpose in the Psalter.',
        18: 'HEBREW: "You alone, whose name is the LORD (YHWH), are the Most High (\'Elyon) over all the earth" — the psalm concludes with the supremacy of YHWH. The enemy nations will discover that the God of Israel is not a local deity but the sovereign over the entire earth. The title \'Elyon (Most High) appears in the divine council context (Ps. 82:6) and in the Melchizedek narrative (Gen. 14:18-22).',
    },
    84: {
        2: 'HEBREW: "How lovely are Your dwelling places" (mah yedidot mishkenotekha) — yedidot means "beloved, lovely, precious." Mishkenot is the plural of mishkan (tabernacle, dwelling). The intense longing for God\'s presence (v.3, "my soul longed and even yearned") uses three Hebrew words for desire: kasaph (longed), kalah (yearned/pined), and ranan (sings for joy). Body and soul together reach toward God.',
        7: 'HEBREW: "The valley of Baca" (\'emeq habBaka\') — Baca means "weeping" or possibly "balsam trees" (which grow in arid places). The pilgrim transforms a valley of tears into a spring of refreshment. The journey to God\'s presence turns suffering into blessing. This is the pilgrim principle: even the difficult road to God becomes a source of life.',
        10: 'HEBREW: "The face of Your anointed" (penei meshichekha) — meshiach (anointed one) here refers to the Davidic king, God\'s representative in worship. The anointed king functions as a mediator of divine blessing, a role that Christ fulfills definitively.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: "A day in Your courts is better than a thousand" — the Hebrew is literally "I have chosen to stand at the threshold (histopheph) of the house of my God rather than dwell (dur) in the tents of wickedness." Histopheph means to stand at the doorstep, the lowest possible position. The psalmist would rather be a doorkeeper in God\'s house than a prince in the world. This radical preference for God\'s presence over worldly comfort is the heart of biblical piety.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The LORD God is a sun and shield" (shemesh umagen YHWH Elohim) — the only place in the OT where God is called a "sun" (shemesh). He is both the source of life/light (sun) and the source of protection (shield). "Grace and glory" (chen wekhavod) — grace for the journey, glory at the destination.',
    },
    85: {
        2: 'HEBREW: "You restored the captivity of Jacob" (shavta shevut Ya\'aqov) — or "You turned the fortunes of Jacob." The phrase shavta shevut can mean return from exile or a broader restoration of fortune. The psalm may reflect the return from Babylonian exile, yet the community still feels incomplete — hence the prayer for full restoration (vv.5-7).',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He will speak peace to His people, to His godly ones" (yedabber shalom \'el \'ammo we\'el chasidav) — God\'s intended word to His people is shalom. The condition: "but let them not turn back to folly" (we\'al yashuvu likhsilah). Peace and foolishness are incompatible. The return to folly would nullify the restoration God has begun.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Lovingkindness and truth have met together; righteousness and peace have kissed each other" (chesed we\'emet nifgashu, tsedeq weshalom nashaquu) — one of the most celebrated verses in the Psalter. Four divine attributes are personified and reconciled: chesed (covenant love), emet (truth/faithfulness), tsedeq (righteousness), and shalom (peace). The tension between justice (which condemns) and mercy (which forgives) is resolved in their embrace. Christian theology sees this fulfilled at the cross, where God\'s righteousness and mercy meet in Christ\'s atoning death (Rom. 3:25-26).',
        12: 'HEBREW: "Truth springs from the earth, and righteousness looks down from heaven" — earth and heaven cooperate in the restoration. Human faithfulness rises to meet divine righteousness. This is the picture of a fully restored cosmos where heaven and earth are reunited.',
    },
    86: {
        5: 'HEBREW: "Ready to forgive" (sallach) — this adjective form appears only here and in Neh. 9:17. It means God is characteristically disposed toward forgiveness. It is not wrung from Him reluctantly; it is His nature.',
        8: 'DIVINE COUNCIL: "There is no one like You among the gods (elohim), O Lord" (\'ein kamokha va\'elohim \'Adonai) — David acknowledges the existence of other elohim while affirming YHWH\'s absolute supremacy. The phrase does not affirm polytheism but rather the divine council worldview: there are spiritual beings called elohim, but none compare to YHWH. This is consistent with Ps. 82:1, 89:6-8, and Deut. 32:8-9.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "All nations whom You have made shall come and worship before You" — a universal eschatological vision. The nations are not destroyed but converted. Their worship of YHWH is the telos (end goal) of creation. This anticipates Rev. 15:4, which quotes this verse in the context of the final consummation.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: "You alone are God" (\'attah Elohim levaddekhah) — this is not a denial of other spiritual beings but an affirmation of YHWH\'s unique status. He alone is Elohim in the supreme sense — creator, sovereign, incomparable. The other elohim are creatures; YHWH alone is uncreated.',
        11: 'HEBREW: "Unite my heart to fear Your name" (yached levavi leyir\'ah shemekha) — yached means to unite, to make one. The human heart is fractured, divided in its loyalties. David asks God to integrate his inner life around a single focus: reverence for God\'s name. This is the prayer for wholeness and singularity of devotion.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "A God merciful and gracious, slow to anger and abundant in lovingkindness and truth" (\'El rachum wechannun \'erekh \'appayim werav-chesed we\'emet) — David quotes the Exodus 34:6 self-disclosure formula directly. This is the same creedal declaration found in Ps. 103:8.',
    },
    87: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "His foundation is in the holy mountains" (yesudato beharey qodesh) — the psalm opens abruptly with no introduction. "Foundation" (yesudah) implies something established, permanent, divinely rooted. The holy mountains are Zion\'s hills. God chose this as His earthly seat.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: "I shall mention Rahab and Babylon among those who know Me" — Rahab is a poetic name for Egypt (cf. Ps. 89:10; Isa. 30:7). God claims that Israel\'s historic enemies — Egypt, Babylon, Philistia, Tyre, Ethiopia — will be registered as citizens of Zion. This is a stunning prophecy of Gentile inclusion in God\'s people (cf. Isa. 19:23-25; Eph. 2:11-22).',
        5: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "Of Zion it shall be said, \'This one and that one were born in her\'" — spiritual birth in Zion transcends ethnicity. This anticipates Jesus\' teaching that one must be "born from above" to enter the kingdom (John 3:3-7). Paul declares: "The Jerusalem above is free; she is our mother" (Gal. 4:26). Citizenship in God\'s city is by new birth, not geography.',
    },
    88: {
        1: 'HEBREW: Attributed to Heman the Ezrahite (cf. 1 Kings 4:31; 1 Chron. 6:33). This is the darkest psalm in the Psalter — it begins in anguish and ends in darkness (v.19). Unlike other laments, it contains no turn to praise, no resolution, no light. Yet it IS prayer — every verse is addressed to God. Faith persists even in unrelieved suffering.',
        7: 'HEBREW: "The lowest pit" (bor tachtiyyot) — three descending images: pit, dark places, depths. The psalmist feels submerged beneath multiple layers of divine wrath. "All Your waves" (\'al kol mishbarekha) — the same word (mishbar) used in Jonah 2:3, where the prophet in the fish\'s belly says "All Your breakers and waves passed over me."',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Will Your lovingkindness be declared in the grave (sheol)?" — a series of rhetorical questions (vv.11-13) exploring whether the dead can praise God. The implied answer is no: Sheol is a place of silence and forgetfulness. This reflects the limited Old Testament understanding of the afterlife before the fuller revelation of resurrection (Dan. 12:2; John 11:25-26).',
        15: 'HEBREW: "Why do You reject my soul? Why do You hide Your face from me?" — two accusations hurled at God. The psalmist does not ask what he did wrong; he asks why God acts as He does. The assumption is not personal guilt but divine mystery. This is lament at its rawest — demanding an explanation from God and receiving silence.',
        19: 'HEBREW: "My acquaintances are in darkness" (meyudda\'ai machshakh) — the final word of the psalm is machshakh, "darkness." No resolution, no dawn. This is the psalm\'s brutal honesty. Some scholars see in it a foreshadowing of Christ\'s experience of God-forsakenness on the cross (Matt. 27:46), where the sinless one entered total darkness on behalf of sinners.',
    },
    89: {
        2: 'HEBREW: "I will sing of the lovingkindness of the LORD forever" (chasdey YHWH \'olam \'ashirah) — chesed (lovingkindness, covenant loyalty) and \'emunah (faithfulness) are the twin pillars of the psalm. These two words dominate vv.1-37, making this the greatest sustained meditation on God\'s covenant faithfulness in the Psalter.',
        4: 'DAVIDIC COVENANT: "I have made a covenant with My chosen; I have sworn to David My servant" (karatti verit livechiri nishba\'ti leDavid \'avdi) — this is the Psalm\'s summary of 2 Sam. 7:8-16, the Davidic covenant. The key promises: eternal seed (zera\', v.5), eternal throne (kisse\', v.5). This covenant is unconditional — even if David\'s sons sin (vv.31-33), God will not revoke it (vv.34-35). The NT identifies Jesus as the ultimate fulfillment of this covenant (Luke 1:32-33; Acts 2:29-36; Rev. 22:16).',
        6: 'DIVINE COUNCIL: "The heavens will praise Your wonders, O LORD; Your faithfulness also in the assembly of the holy ones (qehal qedoshim)" — the "holy ones" (qedoshim) are the members of the divine council. Verse 7 makes this explicit: "who in the skies (shachaq) is comparable to the LORD? Who among the sons of the mighty (benei elim) is like the LORD?" Benei elim literally means "sons of gods" or "sons of the mighty ones" — these are divine beings, the same class as the elohim of Ps. 82 and the benei ha\'elohim of Job 1:6.',
        7: 'DIVINE COUNCIL: "Who among the sons of the mighty (benei elim) is like the LORD" — this is a rhetorical question expecting the answer "no one." The divine council members are real, powerful beings, but YHWH is incomparably greater. Verse 8 continues: "a God greatly feared in the council of the holy ones (sod qedoshim)" — sod means "council, secret assembly, intimate circle." God presides over this council with absolute authority. The other members fear Him because He is "awesome above all those who are around Him."',
        11: 'HEBREW: "You Yourself crushed Rahab like one who is slain" (dikkita kechalal Rahav) — Rahab (not the woman of Jericho) is the chaos monster representing Egypt and all forces of primordial evil (cf. Isa. 51:9; Job 9:13; 26:12). God\'s victory over Rahab at creation and at the Exodus are merged into a single declaration of cosmic sovereignty.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Righteousness and justice are the foundation of Your throne; lovingkindness and truth go before You" — the four-fold foundation of divine rule: tsedeq (righteousness), mishpat (justice), chesed (lovingkindness), \'emet (truth). These same attributes appear personified in Ps. 85:10-11. God\'s throne rests on moral reality.',
        27: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "He will cry to Me, \'You are my Father, my God, and the rock of my salvation\'" — the Davidic king calls God "Father" (\'avi). This father-son relationship between God and the king (cf. 2 Sam. 7:14; Ps. 2:7) is fulfilled supremely in Jesus, who is both David\'s son and God\'s eternal Son (Matt. 22:41-46; Heb. 1:5).',
        28: 'HEBREW: "I also shall make him My firstborn (bekhor)" — bekhor does not necessarily mean first in birth order but first in rank and privilege. Applied to David\'s line, it means the Davidic king holds preeminence among all kings. Applied to Christ, it finds its fullest expression in Col. 1:15 ("the firstborn of all creation") and Rev. 1:5 ("the firstborn of the dead").',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: "My covenant I will not violate, nor will I alter the utterance of My lips" (beriti lo\' \'achallel umotsa\' sephattai lo\' \'ashanneh) — the strongest possible guarantee: God stakes His own holiness (v.36) on the permanence of the Davidic covenant. This creates the psalm\'s agonizing tension: if the covenant is irrevocable, why does reality (vv.39-52) look like covenant failure?',
        39: 'THEOLOGICAL: The psalm\'s dramatic turn. After 38 verses of covenant celebration, vv.39-52 are a devastating lament. God seems to have broken His own covenant — the king is defeated, the crown profaned, the walls broken. This tension between promise and reality is one of the deepest in Scripture. It is resolved only in the resurrection of the Davidic Messiah (Acts 2:25-36; 13:32-37).',
        49: 'HEBREW: "What man can live and not see death?" (mi gever yichyeh welo\' yir\'eh-mavet) — the existential question that the Davidic covenant itself raises. If the king dies, how can the throne be eternal? The answer is resurrection. Only a king who conquers death can fulfill the promise of an everlasting dynasty (Acts 2:29-32; 13:34-37).',
        52: 'THEOLOGICAL: "With which they have reproached the footsteps of Your anointed" (\'iqvot meshichekhah) — the final verse before the doxology. The anointed\'s "footsteps" (\'iqvot) suggest his path, his journey, his coming. Some read this messianically: the enemies mock the very idea that God\'s anointed will come. But the doxology (v.53) answers with affirmation: "Blessed be the LORD forever!"',
        53: 'HEBREW: "Blessed be the LORD forever! Amen and Amen" — this doxology closes Book III of the Psalter (Pss. 73-89). The entire Book III grapples with crisis — the fall of the monarchy, the destruction of the Temple — and ends not with resolution but with praise amid unanswered questions. Faith declares "Amen" even when understanding fails.',
    },
    90: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "A Prayer of Moses, the man of God" (tephillah leMosheh \'ish ha\'Elohim) — the only psalm attributed to Moses, making it potentially the oldest composition in the Psalter. "Lord, You have been our dwelling place" (ma\'on) — God Himself is Israel\'s home, not any physical location. This was especially meaningful for a generation that wandered forty years without a permanent dwelling.',
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: "From everlasting to everlasting, You are God" (me\'olam \'ad \'olam \'attah El) — one of the most direct statements of God\'s eternality in Scripture. Before creation, God was. After all things pass, God will be. The verb "gave birth" (techolel, from chul, to writhe in labor) applies creation language to the earth and world — God brought them forth.',
        3: 'HEBREW: "You turn man back into dust" (tashev \'enosh \'ad-dakka\') — echoes Gen. 3:19 ("to dust you shall return"). The command "Return" (shuvu) is both judgment and invitation. God\'s authority over human mortality is absolute.',
        4: 'HEBREW: "A thousand years in Your sight are like yesterday" (\'eleph shanim be\'eynekha keyom \'etmol) — the radical disproportion between divine and human time. Peter quotes this principle in 2 Pet. 3:8 to explain the apparent delay of Christ\'s return. God\'s patience operates on a timescale incomprehensible to mortals.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: "You have placed our iniquities before You, our secret sins in the light of Your countenance" (\'alumenu lim\'or panekha) — \'alumim means hidden, concealed things. Nothing is hidden from God\'s face. The light of His presence (\'or panim) exposes what darkness conceals. This is both terrifying (no sin escapes notice) and liberating (confession brings what is hidden into healing light).',
        10: 'HEBREW: "The days of our life contain seventy years, or if due to strength, eighty years" (yemey shenotenu bahem shiv\'im shanah we\'im bigvurot shemonim shanah) — the most famous statement of human lifespan in Scripture. "Their pride" (rohbam) means their best part, their crowning achievement. Even the peak of human life is "labor and sorrow" (\'amal wa\'aven). "Soon it is gone and we fly away" (ki gaz chish wanna\'uphah) — the brevity and speed of human transience.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Teach us to number our days" (limnot yameynu ken hoda\') — the practical conclusion of the psalm. If life is brief (vv.3-11) and God is eternal (vv.1-2), then wisdom consists of living in light of that proportion. "A heart of wisdom" (levav chokhmah) comes from reckoning honestly with mortality.',
        17: 'HEBREW: "The favor of the Lord our God" (no\'am \'Adonai \'Elohenu) — no\'am means pleasantness, beauty, graciousness. Moses asks not merely for survival but for God\'s beauty to rest upon His people. "Confirm the work of our hands" (ma\'aseh yadenu konenah) — repeated twice for emphasis. Human labor has meaning only when God establishes it.',
    },
    91: {
        1: 'HEBREW: Four names for God in vv.1-2: \'Elyon (Most High), Shaddai (Almighty), YHWH (the LORD), Elohai (my God). The psalm stacks divine titles to emphasize the comprehensive nature of God\'s protection. "The shelter of the Most High" (seter \'Elyon) — seter means hiding place, secret place, covert.',
        4: 'HEBREW: "His pinions... His wings" (\'evrato... kenaphayv) — God is depicted as a mother bird sheltering her young (cf. Deut. 32:11; Ruth 2:12; Matt. 23:37). "His faithfulness is a shield and bulwark" (tsinnah vesocharah \'amitto) — \'emunah (faithfulness) is both defensive armor (shield) and fortification (bulwark, rampart).',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: The comprehensive list of threats neutralized — terror by night, arrows by day, pestilence in darkness, destruction at noon (vv.5-6) — covers all times and circumstances. No hour is unprotected. The poetic structure implies total coverage: night/day, darkness/noon.',
        9: 'HEBREW: "You have made the LORD, my refuge" (ki \'attah YHWH machsi) — the shift from third person description (vv.1-8) to second person address makes the psalm personal. The conditional nature of the protection is implied: it belongs to the one who has made the LORD his dwelling.',
        11: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "For He will give His angels charge concerning you, to guard you in all your ways" — Satan quotes this verse (and v.12) to Jesus during the temptation (Matt. 4:6; Luke 4:10-11), omitting "in all your ways" to twist the promise into a justification for presumption. Jesus responds with Deut. 6:16: "You shall not put the LORD your God to the test." The psalm\'s promise is real, but Satan\'s application was a perversion — demanding miraculous protection rather than trusting in God\'s sovereign care.',
        13: 'HEBREW: "You will tread upon the lion and cobra" (\'al shachal wapeten tidrakh) — four dangerous creatures: lion (shachal), cobra (peten), young lion (kephir), serpent (tannin). The imagery of treading on serpents connects to Gen. 3:15 (the seed of the woman will crush the serpent\'s head) and to Jesus\' statement in Luke 10:19: "I have given you authority to tread on serpents and scorpions."',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: God speaks directly in vv.14-16 — the psalm\'s climax. The conditions for protection are named: love (chashaq, v.14), knowing God\'s name (v.14), calling upon Him (v.15). The rewards: deliverance, exaltation, answered prayer, presence in trouble, rescue, honor, long life, and salvation. These eight promises constitute the fullest statement of divine protection in the Psalter.',
    },
    92: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "For the Sabbath day" (leyom hashabbat) — the only psalm explicitly designated for the Sabbath. Jewish tradition assigns it to the Sabbath liturgy. The psalm\'s themes of praise, the downfall of the wicked, and the flourishing of the righteous reflect the Sabbath\'s eschatological significance — the rest that anticipates the world to come.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: "When the wicked sprouted up like grass and all who did iniquity flourished, it was only that they might be destroyed forevermore" — the same problem as Ps. 73, but here the answer is given immediately. The wicked flourish only temporarily, like grass (cf. Ps. 90:5-6; Isa. 40:6-8). Their apparent prosperity is actually the prelude to their destruction.',
        13: 'HEBREW: "The righteous man will flourish like the palm tree; he will grow like a cedar in Lebanon" (tsaddiq kattamar yifrach ke\'erez balLevanon yisgeh) — two trees contrasted with the grass of v.8. The palm (tamar) is fruitful and resilient; the cedar (\'erez) is massive, durable, and long-lived. Both represent the enduring vitality of the righteous.',
    },
    93: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The LORD reigns" (YHWH malakh) — this declaration opens the enthronement psalms (93, 96-99). The Hebrew can also be translated "The LORD has become king" or "The LORD is king." The affirmation that YHWH reigns is set against the backdrop of chaos (the floods, v.3) that threatens to overwhelm creation. God\'s kingship is established precisely in His victory over chaos.',
    },
    94: {
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He who planted the ear, does He not hear? He who formed the eye, does He not see?" — a devastating argument from design. The Creator of the senses possesses those senses infinitely. It is absurd to think the One who invented hearing is deaf or the One who invented sight is blind. This is the classic argument against practical atheism.',
        11: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "The LORD knows the thoughts of man, that they are a mere breath" (hevel) — Paul quotes this in 1 Cor. 3:20 to demonstrate the futility of human wisdom apart from God. Hevel (breath, vapor, vanity) is the key word of Ecclesiastes.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Blessed is the man whom You chasten, O LORD" (\'ashrey haggever asher teyasserennu Yah) — discipline (yasar) is a mark of sonship, not rejection. The same principle in Prov. 3:11-12 is quoted in Heb. 12:5-11. Chastening produces "the peaceful fruit of righteousness" (Heb. 12:11).',
        19: 'HEBREW: "When my anxious thoughts multiply within me, Your consolations delight my soul" (berov sar\'appay beqirbi tanchu-meykha yesha\'ash\'u nafshi) — sar\'appim means disquieting, anxious thoughts (the word appears only here and in Ps. 139:23). God\'s consolations (tanchumim) are the antidote. The psalm moves from corporate justice (vv.1-15) to personal testimony (vv.16-23).',
    },
    95: {
        7: 'THEOLOGICAL / CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "Today, if you would hear His voice, do not harden your hearts" — this is one of the most extensively quoted OT passages in the NT. Hebrews 3:7-11 attributes these words directly to the Holy Spirit and applies them to the church. Heb. 3:13, 15; 4:7 repeat "Today" as an urgent call. The warning is against the same unbelief that prevented the Exodus generation from entering the promised land. The author of Hebrews argues that a "rest" (katapausis, corresponding to menuchah) remains for God\'s people, and "today" is always the day to respond in faith.',
        8: 'HEBREW: "Meribah" (merivah = "strife, contention") and "Massah" (massah = "testing, trial") — the place names encode Israel\'s failure (Exod. 17:1-7). They tested God despite having seen His works for forty years (v.10). The lesson: witnessing miracles does not guarantee faithfulness; only a responsive heart does.',
    },
    96: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Sing to the LORD a new song" (shiru laYHWH shir chadash) — the command to sing a "new song" (shir chadash) appears in Pss. 33:3; 40:3; 96:1; 98:1; 144:9; 149:1; Isa. 42:10; Rev. 5:9; 14:3. Each new act of God demands a new response. Old songs are not sufficient for new revelations of divine power.',
        5: 'HEBREW: "All the gods of the peoples are idols" (kol \'elohey ha\'ammim \'elilim) — a devastating wordplay. The gods (elohim) of the nations are \'elilim (worthless things, nothings, idols). The word \'elilim sounds like elohim but means the opposite. The true God made the heavens (shamayim); the false gods are nothing.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The LORD reigns" (YHWH malakh) — the enthronement cry. "He will judge the peoples with equity" (meysharim) — God\'s coming is not just for Israel but for all peoples. The cosmic joy of vv.11-13 (heavens, earth, sea, field, trees) anticipates the renewal of all creation at God\'s coming (Rom. 8:19-22).',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: "For He is coming to judge the earth" (ki va\' lishpot ha\'arets) — repeated "He is coming" (ki va\', ki va\') doubles the emphasis. God\'s coming judgment is not a threat but a hope: creation rejoices because God\'s judgment means the end of injustice and the renewal of all things. The trees and seas do not fear the Judge; they celebrate Him.',
    },
    97: {
        7: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "Worship Him, all you gods" (hishtachawu lo kol \'elohim) — the Septuagint renders this as "Worship Him, all His angels." The author of Hebrews quotes this version in Heb. 1:6 to demonstrate Christ\'s superiority to angels: "And when He again brings the firstborn into the world, He says, \'And let all the angels of God worship Him.\'" The divine beings who compose God\'s council are commanded to worship the incarnate Son.',
    },
    98: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "His right hand and His holy arm have gained the victory for Him" (hoshi\'ah lo yemino uzeroa\' qodsho) — God\'s salvation is His own achievement, not dependent on human effort. The "new song" (shir chadash) signals a new act of divine deliverance that demands fresh praise.',
    },
    99: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He is enthroned above the cherubim" (yoshev hakeruvim) — the same title as Ps. 80:2. The cherubim throne represents God\'s sovereign rule over all creation. "Let the peoples tremble" (yirgezu \'ammim) — God\'s reign provokes awe and fear among the nations. The threefold "holy" declaration (vv.3, 5, 9) echoes the seraphim\'s cry in Isa. 6:3.',
    },
    100: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "A Psalm for Thanksgiving" (mizmor lethodah) — the todah (thanksgiving) offering (Lev. 7:12-15) accompanied communal praise. This psalm may have been composed for the todah ceremony at the Temple. Its brevity (5 verses) and universal scope ("all the earth," v.1) make it one of the most accessible psalms in the Psalter.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Know that the LORD Himself is God; it is He who has made us, and not we ourselves" (de\'u ki-YHWH hu\' Elohim, hu\' \'asanu welo\' \'anachnu) — a fundamental creedal statement. The Qere (reading tradition) has lo\' with aleph ("not"), making it "He made us and not we ourselves." The Ketiv (written text) has lo with vav ("His"), yielding "He made us and we are His." Both readings are theologically true and complementary. We are creatures, not self-made; we belong to God.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: "For the LORD is good; His lovingkindness is everlasting and His faithfulness to all generations" (ki-tov YHWH le\'olam chasdo we\'ad-dor wador \'emunato) — the three attributes summarize God\'s character: goodness (tov), lovingkindness (chesed), and faithfulness (\'emunah). Each extends without limit: goodness is God\'s nature, chesed is everlasting (le\'olam), and faithfulness reaches to all generations (\'ad-dor wador).',
    },
    101: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: A royal psalm of commitment — David\'s "oath of office." The king pledges personal integrity (v.2), purity of vision (v.3), separation from evil (vv.4-5), and righteous governance (vv.6-8). This is the ideal of Davidic kingship that no human king fully achieved, pointing forward to Christ the righteous King.',
    },
    102: {
        1: 'HEBREW: The superscription "A Prayer of the afflicted when he is faint and pours out his complaint before the LORD" is one of the longest in the Psalter. The Hebrew \'ani (afflicted, poor) describes someone crushed by circumstances and crying out to God from the depths.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: "But You, O LORD, abide forever" (we\'attah YHWH le\'olam teshev) — the psalm\'s pivot. Verses 2-12 describe human transience (smoke, scorched bones, withered grass, lengthened shadow). Verse 12 introduces the contrast: God endures forever. The psalmist\'s mortality heightens the glory of God\'s eternality.',
        14: 'HEBREW: "The appointed time has come" (ki-va\' mo\'ed) — mo\'ed means appointed time, set meeting. God\'s compassion on Zion operates on a divine timetable. The promise is not merely that God will act, but that He has appointed a specific time for restoration. This is the biblical principle of kairos — God\'s decisive moment.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: "This will be written for the generation to come, that a people yet to be created may praise the LORD" — the psalmist writes not for himself but for the future. "A people yet to be created" (\'am nivra\') — the verb bara\' (create, the same verb as Gen. 1:1) suggests that this future praising people will be a new creation of God, not merely a future generation.',
        25: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "Of old You founded the earth, and the heavens are the work of Your hands" — Hebrews 1:10-12 quotes vv.25-27 and applies them directly to Christ, the Son. The author of Hebrews takes a psalm addressed to YHWH and attributes its words to the Son, demonstrating that the Son is the Creator who endures when all creation perishes. This is one of the strongest NT affirmations of Christ\'s deity and eternality.',
        27: 'HEBREW: "Like clothing You will change them and they will be changed" (kallevush tachalifem weyachalofu) — the heavens and earth are likened to worn-out garments that God will replace. "But You are the same" (we\'attah hu\') — the pronoun hu\' ("He," here "the same") is almost a divine name, expressing God\'s unchanging identity. This is applied to Christ in Heb. 1:12 and 13:8: "Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever."',
    },
    103: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Bless the LORD, O my soul" (barekhi nafshi \'et-YHWH) — the psalm opens and closes with this summons (vv.1-2, 22). Unlike most psalms that ask God to bless the worshiper, here the worshiper blesses God. Barakh means to kneel in homage, to speak well of, to praise. The soul (nephesh) and "all that is within me" (kol qeravai) indicate total, interior worship.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: Five benefits of God in vv.3-5: pardoning iniquity, healing disease, redeeming from the pit, crowning with lovingkindness, satisfying with good things. These move from negative (removal of sin and sickness) to positive (redemption, honor, satisfaction). The list is not exhaustive but representative of God\'s comprehensive care for the whole person.',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The LORD is compassionate and gracious, slow to anger and abounding in lovingkindness" (rachum wechannun YHWH, \'erekh \'appayim werav-chesed) — this is the great self-disclosure formula from Exod. 34:6-7, the most frequently quoted creedal statement in the Old Testament. It appears in Neh. 9:17; Joel 2:13; Jonah 4:2; Nah. 1:3; Pss. 86:15; 145:8. It is the closest thing to a systematic theology of God\'s character in the Hebrew Bible.',
        12: 'HEBREW: "As far as the east is from the west" (kirchoq mizrach mimma\'arav) — an immeasurable distance, since east and west never meet. This is the psalm\'s supreme image of forgiveness: our sins are placed at infinite remove from us. Unlike north and south, which have poles, east and west are perpetually divergent.',
        14: 'HEBREW: "He Himself knows our frame" (hu\' yada\' yitsrenu) — yetser means formation, frame, what is formed. The same root appears in Gen. 2:7 where God "formed" (yatsar) man from dust. God knows our material — He made it. "He is mindful that we are but dust" (zakur ki-\'aphar \'anachnu) — dust (\'aphar) echoes Gen. 2:7 and 3:19. God\'s compassion is grounded in His knowledge of human fragility.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The LORD has established His throne in the heavens, and His sovereignty rules over all" (YHWH bashamayim hekhin kis\'o umalkhuto bakkol mashalah) — the psalm moves from personal experience (vv.1-5) to national history (vv.6-7) to theological reflection (vv.8-18) to cosmic sovereignty (vv.19-22). The final horizon is the widest: all creation is summoned to praise.',
        20: 'DIVINE COUNCIL: "Bless the LORD, you His angels (mal\'akhav), mighty in strength, who perform His word" — the angels are summoned to bless God alongside human worshipers. "Mighty in strength" (gibborey koach) indicates these are powerful beings. They "perform His word" — their obedience is instantaneous and complete. This verse gives us a glimpse of the heavenly worship that parallels and surpasses earthly worship.',
    },
    104: {
        2: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Covering Yourself with light as with a cloak" (\'oteh-\'or kassalmah) — God\'s first act of self-revelation is light (Gen. 1:3). The psalm follows the creation order of Genesis 1: light (v.2), firmament/waters (vv.2-4), dry land (vv.5-9), vegetation (vv.14-16), luminaries (v.19), sea creatures (v.25-26), provision (vv.27-28). This is the poetic counterpart to the Genesis 1 narrative.',
        4: 'HEBREW: "He makes the winds His messengers, flaming fire His ministers" (\'oseh mal\'akhav ruchot mesharetav \'esh lohet) — Heb. 1:7 quotes this to contrast angels (who are created servants) with the Son (who is eternal Creator, vv.25-27 via Ps. 102). Mal\'akh means both "messenger" and "angel." Ruach means both "wind" and "spirit." The ambiguity is theologically rich.',
        5: 'HEBREW: "He established the earth upon its foundations" (yasad \'erets \'al mekhoneha) — the language of architectural foundation. The earth is presented as a stable structure built by a master builder. "It will not totter forever and ever" (bal timmot \'olam wa\'ed) — God\'s creation is fundamentally stable because He is its foundation.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He made the moon for the seasons; the sun knows the place of its setting" — the luminaries serve God\'s purposes. They are not deities (as in surrounding cultures) but servants. The moon marks mo\'adim (appointed times, festivals), connecting astronomy to liturgy. The sun "knows" its place — even celestial bodies obey their Creator.',
        24: 'HEBREW: "O LORD, how many are Your works! In wisdom You have made them all" (mah rabbu ma\'asekha YHWH kullam bechokhmah \'asita) — the exclamation at the midpoint of the psalm. Wisdom (chokhmah) is the master principle of creation (cf. Prov. 8:22-31, where Wisdom personified participates in creation). Everything bears the stamp of intelligent design.',
        26: 'HEBREW: "Leviathan, which You have formed to sport in it" (Livyatan zeh yatsarta lesacheq-bo) — Leviathan appears here not as a chaos monster to be defeated (as in Ps. 74:14; Isa. 27:1) but as God\'s plaything, created for sport. The sea, which terrified ancient peoples, is merely God\'s toy box. This is one of the most audacious statements of divine sovereignty in Scripture (cf. Job 41).',
        29: 'THEOLOGICAL: "You hide Your face, they are dismayed; You take away their spirit, they expire and return to their dust" — all life depends moment by moment on God\'s sustaining will. Creation is not self-sustaining; it exists only because God continually wills it. Withdrawal of divine attention means immediate death and return to dust (Gen. 3:19).',
        30: 'HEBREW: "You send forth Your Spirit, they are created" (teshalach ruchakhah yibbarre\'un) — ruach (Spirit/breath) is the agent of both creation and renewal. This parallels Gen. 1:2 ("the Spirit of God was moving over the surface of the waters") and anticipates the new creation by the Spirit (Ezek. 37:9-14; Rom. 8:11).',
        35: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Let sinners be consumed from the earth" — the only imprecatory note in this praise psalm. Sin is the one element that does not belong in God\'s good creation. The prayer for the removal of sinners is a prayer for creation to be fully what God intended. "Praise the LORD" (Halleluyah) — this is the first occurrence of Halleluyah in the Psalter.',
    },
    105: {
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He has remembered His covenant forever" (zakhar le\'olam berito) — the verb zakhar (remember) does not mean God forgot; it means God acts on the basis of His covenant commitment. The psalm traces God\'s faithfulness from Abraham (v.9) through Isaac (v.9), Jacob (v.10), the patriarchal sojourning (vv.12-15), Joseph (vv.16-22), Egypt (vv.23-38), the wilderness (vv.39-41), to the land (vv.44-45). Every event serves the covenant.',
        15: 'HEBREW: "Do not touch My anointed ones (meshichay), and do My prophets no harm" — God protected the patriarchs despite their vulnerability as wandering aliens. "Anointed ones" (meshichim) here refers to the patriarchs themselves, indicating that anointing signifies divine commissioning, not just royal office.',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He sent a man before them, Joseph, who was sold as a slave" — the psalm reveals the hidden logic of providence: Joseph\'s suffering was preparation for Israel\'s salvation. What brothers intended for evil, God intended for good (Gen. 50:20). The timing of God\'s plan precedes human understanding of it.',
        25: 'HEBREW: "He turned their heart to hate His people" (haphakh libbam lisno\' \'ammo) — a startling statement of divine sovereignty over human hearts. God did not merely permit Egyptian hatred but directed it as part of His plan (cf. Exod. 4:21, hardening Pharaoh\'s heart). The moral tension is unresolved in the psalm; it simply affirms that God orchestrates all things for His redemptive purposes.',
        39: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He spread a cloud for a covering, and fire to illumine by night" — the pillar of cloud and fire (Exod. 13:21-22) represented continuous divine presence. God did not merely lead Israel; He covered and illuminated them. The covering (masakh) suggests a canopy or tent — God Himself was Israel\'s shelter in the desert.',
    },
    106: {
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: "We have sinned like our fathers" (chatanu \'im \'avotenu) — unlike Ps. 105 which celebrates God\'s faithfulness, Ps. 106 confesses Israel\'s unfaithfulness. Together the two psalms present the full picture: God\'s covenant fidelity persists despite human covenant failure. The confession "we" includes the current generation with the past.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: "They made a calf in Horeb" (\'asuu \'egel bechorev) — the golden calf incident (Exod. 32). "They exchanged their glory for the image of an ox" (v.20) — Paul echoes this language in Rom. 1:23 to describe humanity\'s universal idolatry: they "exchanged the glory of the incorruptible God for an image." The pattern of exchanging truth for a lie is the fundamental human sin.',
        23: 'HEBREW: "Moses His chosen one stood in the breach" (\'amad bapperets) — Moses as intercessor prevents annihilation (Exod. 32:11-14). "Standing in the breach" (perets = gap in a wall) means positioning oneself between God\'s wrath and the people. This intercessory role anticipates Christ\'s mediatorial work (1 Tim. 2:5; Heb. 7:25).',
        30: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Phinehas stood up and interposed" (wayya\'amod Pinehas wayepalel) — Phinehas\'s action at Baal-peor (Num. 25) stopped the plague. "It was reckoned to him for righteousness" (watechashev lo litsedaqah) — the same language used of Abraham\'s faith (Gen. 15:6). Righteous action and righteous faith are both "credited" by God.',
        37: 'THEOLOGICAL: "They even sacrificed their sons and their daughters to the demons" (shedim) — the word shedim (demons) appears only here and in Deut. 32:17 in the Hebrew Bible. Child sacrifice to Molech (Lev. 18:21; 20:2-5; 2 Kings 23:10; Jer. 32:35) is reinterpreted as worship of demons. Behind the idol stands a demonic reality. Paul makes the same connection in 1 Cor. 10:20.',
        44: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Nevertheless He looked upon their distress when He heard their cry" — the word "nevertheless" (wayyar\') is the psalm\'s theological hinge. Despite the comprehensive catalog of sin (vv.6-43), God\'s compassion is not exhausted. He remembered His covenant (v.45). This is the miracle of grace: not that sin is excused, but that covenant love persists through it.',
        48: 'HEBREW: "Blessed be the LORD, the God of Israel, from everlasting even to everlasting" — this doxology closes Book IV of the Psalter (Pss. 90-106). Each of the five books of the Psalter ends with a doxology (41:13; 72:18-19; 89:52; 106:48; Ps. 150 as final doxology). "Amen and Amen" (\'amen we\'amen) — the congregation\'s ratification of the praise.',
    },
    107: {
        1: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Oh give thanks to the LORD, for He is good" (hodu laYHWH ki-tov) — this refrain opens Book V of the Psalter (Pss. 107-150). The psalm uses four vignettes of distress and deliverance (wanderers vv.4-9, prisoners vv.10-16, the sick vv.17-22, sailors vv.23-32), each ending with the same refrain: "Let them give thanks to the LORD for His lovingkindness" (vv.8, 15, 21, 31).',
        2: 'HEBREW: "Let the redeemed of the LORD say so" (yomeru ge\'uley YHWH) — ge\'ulim (redeemed ones, from ga\'al) are those whom God has acted as kinsman-redeemer (go\'el) to deliver. The command to "say so" makes testimony a duty, not merely an option. Those who have experienced redemption are obligated to declare it.',
        20: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "He sent His word and healed them" (yishlach devaro weyirpa\'em) — God\'s word is the agent of healing. In John 1:1-4, 14, the Word (Logos) becomes flesh and brings life. Jesus heals by His word (Matt. 8:8, 16), fulfilling this pattern.',
        29: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He caused the storm to be still, so that the waves of the sea were hushed" — Jesus\' calming of the storm (Mark 4:39, "Peace, be still!") directly parallels this verse. The disciples\' response — "Who then is this, that even the wind and the sea obey Him?" — is answered by Ps. 107: the one who calms the storm is the LORD Himself.',
        43: 'HEBREW: "Who is wise? Let him give heed to these things" (mi chakkam weyishmor \'elleh) — the psalm concludes with a wisdom challenge. The four vignettes are not just stories but patterns. The wise person recognizes in them the chesed (lovingkindness) of the LORD operating in all circumstances.',
    },
    108: {
        8: 'HEBREW: This psalm combines portions of Ps. 57:7-11 (vv.1-5) and Ps. 60:5-12 (vv.6-13). "God has spoken in His holiness" (Elohim dibber beqodsho) — the divine oracle that follows (vv.8-10) declares God\'s sovereignty over the entire land and all surrounding nations. Moab as a "washbowl" and Edom receiving God\'s "shoe" are images of menial servitude and territorial claim.',
    },
    109: {
        4: 'HEBREW: "In return for my love they act as my accusers" (tachat \'ahavati yistenuni) — the verb satan (to accuse, to oppose) gives us the noun Satan (the Accuser). David is being "sataned" — opposed and accused — for his love. This echoes the experience of Christ, who was accused by those He loved.',
        6: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Let an accuser (satan) stand at his right hand" — the right hand was the position of the advocate or prosecutor in a legal proceeding. David asks that his enemy face the same accusation he has endured. The imprecatory section (vv.6-19) is one of the longest in the Psalter. These curses invoke God as judge, not personal revenge.',
        8: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "Let his days be few; let another take his office" (piquddato yiqqach \'acher) — Peter quotes this verse in Acts 1:20 and applies it to Judas Iscariot, justifying the appointment of a replacement apostle. Piquddah means office, position of oversight, charge. The Greek episkopos (bishop, overseer) in Acts 1:20 translates this Hebrew concept.',
        21: 'HEBREW: "But You, O GOD, the Lord, deal kindly with me for Your name\'s sake" (we\'attah YHWH \'Adonai \'aseh \'itti lema\'an shemekha) — the shift from imprecation against enemies (vv.6-20) to petition for mercy (vv.21-29) is dramatic. David does not rely on his own righteousness but on God\'s name and lovingkindness (chesed).',
        31: 'THEOLOGICAL: "He stands at the right hand of the needy" (ya\'amod limin \'evyon) — a beautiful reversal of v.6 where a satan stands at the enemy\'s right hand to accuse. God stands at the needy man\'s right hand to defend. Where Satan accuses, God advocates. The psalm closes with divine advocacy triumphing over human accusation.',
    },
    110: {
        1: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY / DIVINE COUNCIL: "The LORD (YHWH) says to my Lord (\'Adoni): Sit at My right hand until I make Your enemies a footstool for Your feet" — this is the single most-quoted Old Testament verse in the New Testament (Matt. 22:44; 26:64; Mark 12:36; 14:62; 16:19; Luke 20:42-43; 22:69; Acts 2:34-35; Rom. 8:34; 1 Cor. 15:25; Eph. 1:20; Col. 3:1; Heb. 1:3, 13; 8:1; 10:12-13; 12:2). David, the king, calls someone "my Lord" (\'Adoni). Jesus uses this to demonstrate that the Messiah is not merely David\'s descendant but David\'s Lord — a being of higher ontological status (Matt. 22:41-46). The two "Lords" are YHWH (the Father) and \'Adoni (the Messiah). The Messiah is invited to share God\'s throne — the highest honor in the universe. "Sit at My right hand" is the position of co-regency and shared authority. No angel is ever offered this seat (Heb. 1:13). The "footstool" imagery derives from ancient Near Eastern conquest ritual where a victorious king placed his foot on the neck of defeated enemies (Josh. 10:24).',
        2: 'HEBREW: "The LORD will stretch forth Your strong scepter from Zion" (matteh \'uzzekhah yishlach YHWH mitstsiyyon) — Zion is the launching point of messianic rule. The scepter (matteh) fulfills Gen. 49:10: "The scepter shall not depart from Judah... until Shiloh comes." The Messiah rules not in a distant heaven but "in the midst of Your enemies" — present, active, and triumphant.',
        3: 'HEBREW: "Your people will volunteer freely in the day of Your power" (\'ammekhah nedavot beyom chelekhah) — nedavot means freewill offerings or willing volunteers. In the Messiah\'s kingdom, obedience is not coerced but freely given. "From the womb of the dawn" (merechem mishchar) — poetic imagery suggesting the Messiah\'s origin is from the dawn of creation itself. "Your youth are to You as the dew" (lekhah tal yaldutekha) — the Messiah\'s followers are innumerable, fresh, and life-giving like morning dew.',
        4: 'CHRIST TYPOLOGY: "The LORD has sworn and will not change His mind: You are a priest forever according to the order of Melchizedek" (nishba\' YHWH welo\' yinnachem \'attah-kohen le\'olam \'al-divrati Malkiy-Tsedeq) — the most theologically significant verse in the psalm alongside v.1. (1) God swears an irrevocable oath — the strongest possible guarantee. (2) The Messiah is declared a priest — but NOT a Levitical priest. (3) "According to the order of Melchizedek" — Melchizedek (Gen. 14:18-20) was king of Salem AND priest of God Most High, predating and superseding the Aaronic priesthood. The author of Hebrews devotes three chapters (5-7) to this verse, arguing that Jesus is a superior high priest: eternal (not subject to death, Heb. 7:23-24), sinless (Heb. 7:26-27), and operating under a better covenant (Heb. 7:22). The union of king and priest in one person was forbidden under the Mosaic law (Uzziah was struck with leprosy for attempting it, 2 Chron. 26:16-21), but Melchizedek held both offices — and so does the Messiah. This is the psalm that establishes Christ as both King (v.1-3) and Priest (v.4) — the two offices united in one eternal person.',
        5: 'HEBREW: "The Lord (\'Adonai) is at Your right hand" — a shift from v.1 where the Messiah sits at YHWH\'s right hand. Now \'Adonai (which could refer to either YHWH or the Messiah) is at the warrior\'s right hand, indicating mutual support in battle. The Messiah and God operate in perfect concert.',
        7: 'HEBREW: "He will drink from the brook by the wayside; therefore He will lift up His head" (minnechal badderekh yishteh \'al-ken yarim ro\'sh) — a striking final image. The victorious warrior-priest-king pauses to drink from a stream during His conquest march, then lifts His head in triumph. Some see this as a picture of humiliation followed by exaltation (Phil. 2:7-9) — the Messiah who stooped low (incarnation, cross) and then was raised to the highest place.',
    },
}
